<TITLE>
Isotopes in Water and Environmental Management
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor=#ffffff>
<H2>
Isotopes in Water and Environmental Management
</H2>
<B>
What Are Isotopes and What Can Be Learned From Them?
</B>
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=0 CELLPADDING=5>
<TR>
<TD>
<IMG BORDER=0 SRC=/worldatom/inforesource/other/gallery/is1.gif> 
<TD>
Collecting water samples for isotope measurements from a well in
Morocco.
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>
<IMG BORDER=0 SRC=/worldatom/inforesource/other/gallery/is2.gif> 
<TD>
Sampling soil from different depths in Senegal using a simple
hand auger.  From the soil sample,
moisture can be extracted and measured for the stable isotope and
tritium contents.
</TD>
</TR>
<TR>
<TD>
<IMG BORDER=0 SRC=/worldatom/inforesource/other/gallery/is3.gif> 
<TD>
In exploiting geothermal energy resources, isotope techniques
help to define the regions of high
heat flow and the origins of fluids.  Deep wells drilled to
depths up to 3 km tap the reservoir to extract the steam and
transport it to the power plant.
</TD>
</TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
