<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Safeguards in the NIS
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H2>Safeguards in the Newly Independent States of the Former USSR </H2>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
By the end of 1994, twelve of the newly independent States had acceded to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT). Three of these (Armenia, Lithuania and Latvia) had concluded safeguards agreements with the Agency and inspections to verify the initial  inventories were carried out. in other States with substantial nuclear programmes:
<UL>
<LI>preparations were made for the implementation of safeguards, with 18 technical visits made to States, including visits to major facilities, parlicularly in Belarus, Kazakhstan and Ukraine;
<LI>preliminary information was obtained regarding nuclear installations, nuclear materials and nuclear material accountancy and control systems;
<LI>safeguards requirements and the need for support by donor States, co-ordinated by the Agency, were identified.
</UL>
<P>
An important part of the Agency's support in 1994 was in the form of training on nuclear material accountancy organized for personnel from national control bodies as well as facilities.In all, there were training events for 218 participants.
<P>
Once initial inspection activities have been completed, the total safeguards effort in the newly independent States is expected to amount to about 6% of the Agency's current total inspection effort.
<P>
<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT20-B02-72</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA060-000326-B017-81</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://nesihp01.iaea.or.at:80/worldatom/inforesource/annual/introbox2.html 193.81.60.210 19970115014703 text/html 3330
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
