<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Chernobyl Conference
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<A HREF=/worldatom/inforesource/pressrelease/prn8.html>
<H2>SECOND ANNOUNCEMENT</H2>
</A>
<P>
<H2>
<FONT SIZE=-1>INTERNATIONAL CONFERENCE</FONT><BR>
ONE DECADE AFTER CHERNOBYL:<BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1>SUMMING UP THE CONSEQUENCES OF THE ACCIDENT</FONT>
</H2>
<P>
Austria Center Vienna, Austria,  8-12 April 1996
<P>
(Preceding the 1996 International Congress on Radiation Protection, IRPA9)
<P>
SPONSORED BY<BR>
<STRONG>
THE EUROPEAN COMMISSION;<BR>
THE INTERNATIONAL ATOMIC ENERGY AGENCY; and,<BR>
THE WORLD HEALTH ORGANIZATION.
</STRONG>
<P>
IN CO-OPERATION WITH<BR>
<STRONG>
THE UNITED NATIONS<BR>
</STRONG>
(DEPARTMENT OF HUMANITARIAN AFFAIRS);<BR>
<STRONG>
THE UNITED NATIONS EDUCATIONAL, SCIENTIFIC AND CULTURAL ORGANIZATION;<BR>
THE UNITED NATIONS ENVIRONMENT PROGRAMME;<BR>
THE UNITED NATIONS SCIENTIFIC COMMITTEE ON THE EFFECTS OF ATOMIC RADIATION;<BR>
THE FOOD AND AGRICULTURE ORGANIZATION OF THE UNITED NATIONS; and<BR>
THE  ORGANISATION FOR ECONOMIC COOPERATION AND DEVELOPMENT<BR>
</STRONG>
(NUCLEAR ENERGY AGENCY)
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
<A HREF=outline.html>OUTLINE OF PROGRAMME</A>
</STRONG>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
</CENTER>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
BACKGROUND
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The consequences attributed to the accident at the Chernobyl nuclear power plant have been subjected to extensive scientific examination; however, they are still viewed with widely differing perspectives. Ten years after the accident, the European Commission (EC), the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and the World Health Organization (WHO) are jointly sponsoring an International Conference to recapitulate the accident's consequences and to seek a common and conclusive understanding of their nature and magnitude. The Conference, One Decade after Chernobyl: Summing Up the Consequences of the Accident, is being organized in co-operation with the United Nations through its Department of Humanitarian Affairs (UNDHA), as well as with the United Nations Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization (UNESCO), the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), the United Nations Scientific Committee on the Effects of Atomic Radiation (UNSCEAR),  the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO), and the Organization for Economic Co-operation and Development through its Nuclear Energy Agency (OECD/NEA), and will take place in the Austria Center Vienna, Austria, from 8 to 12 April 1996.
<P>
The Conference will take particular account of the findings of two prior Conferences. These are: the WHO International Conference on the Health Consequences of the Chernobyl and other Radiological Accidents, to be held in Geneva from 20 to 23 November 1995, and the First International Conference of the European Union, Belarus, the Russian Federation and the Ukraine on the Consequences of the Chernobyl Accident,  to be held in Minsk  from 18 to 22 March 1996.  In addition to including summaries from and being complementary to these prior Conferences, the Conference in Vienna will also address the accident's associated environmental consequences and social, economic and political impacts. It will also consider the outcome of a preceding IAEA/UNDHA International Meeting on the Safety of Chernobyl , which will be held in Vienna from 1-3 April 1996, and will address, among other things, the remedial measures taken since the accident to improve the safety of Chernobyl type reactors and of the containment structure (the so-called sarcophagus) built around the destroyed reactor.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
VENUE AND DATE
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The Conference will take place in the Austria Center Vienna from 8 to 12 April 1996.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
OBJECTIVE
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The Conference will aim at consolidating an international consensus on the consequences of the accident. Important objectives will be to agree on proven scientific facts and to clarify interpretations and prognoses in order to dispel confusion.  In addition, it will aim to quantify the accident's actual consequences, and to review the social, economic and political aftermath, as well as to consider the improvements in nuclear safety that followed the accident. In all these fields the Conference will discuss the prognosis for the future.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
AUDIENCE
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The Conference is mainly directed at  senior technical specialists,  including medical, environmental and engineering experts, mainly in the field of radiation protection and nuclear safety. However, the audience will also embrace opinion formers and, crucially, decision makers who may be faced with taking decisions in the aftermath of a nuclear or radiation accident.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
SCOPE
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The topics to be covered by the Conference are the following:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Health effects attributable to radiation exposure caused by the accident, including:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>clinically observed effects, particularly those in occupationally exposed workers (such as the emergency workers known as liquidators);
<LI>detected thyroid effects;
<LI>epidemiologically quantified and theoretically estimated long term health effects, such as induction of malignancies and hereditary disorders.
</UL>
<P>
<LI>Other health related effects: psychological consequences, mental distress and anxiety.
<LI>Consequences on the environment.
<LI>Social, economic, institutional and political impacts.
<LI>Remedial measures taken to enhance nuclear safety.
<LI>The consequences of the accident put into perspective.
<LI>Prognosis for the future; the Chernobyl sarcophagus.
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
ORGANIZATION
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The Conference will be based on a four tier approach:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>A Briefing Seminar - in four introductory updating sessions  - will summarize the outcome of activities of the sponsoring organizations, largely on the basis of the results of the preceding Conferences, and the co-operating organizations, and also bilateral projects.
<LI>A Technical Symposium - of eight topical sessions and a poster session -  will scientifically examine  the relevant issues, leading into a plenary session for drawing scientific conclusions.
<LI>An Opinion Formers' Session will consider the media impression and the public's perception of the accident's consequences in comparison with their technical description as concluded by the Technical Symposium.
<LI>A Decision Makers' Forum - of three panel sessions - will discuss the implications of the recommendations and conclusions of the Technical Symposium for the decision making process during and after a nuclear or radiation accident.
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
OFFICERS
</CENTER>
</STRONG>
<P>
<UL>
<LI>The highest officer of the Conference will be its President (a senior governmental official of a Member State of the sponsoring organizations will be invited to preside over the Conference).
<P>
<LI>The Directors General of the sponsoring organizations and a representative of the United Nations will open the Conference.
<P>
<LI>A Bureau of senior scientists will assist the President.
<P>
<LI>An Advisory Committee of senior experts from Belarus, the Russian Federation and the Ukraine will monitor the organization and development of the Conference.
<P>
<LI>Chairpersons will moderate and eventually summarize the Briefing Seminar, each topical session of the Technical Symposium, the Opinion Former's Session and each panel session of the Decision Worker's Forum.
<P>
<LI>A Rapporteur will introduce and eventually report on each session of the Technical Seminar.
<P>
<LI>A Joint Secretariat  of the sponsoring organizations, with the assistance of a Scientific Secretariat, will serve the Conference.
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
STAGES
</CENTER>
</STRONG>
<P>
<STRONG>
OPENING SESSION
</STRONG>
<P>
The Opening Session will include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>welcoming remarks by the Directors General of the sponsoring organizations;
<LI>an opening address on behalf of the United Nations by the U.N. Department of Humanitarian Affairs; and
<LI>a keynote speech by the President to state the Conference's objectives.
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
BRIEFING SEMINAR
</STRONG>
<P>
The Briefing Seminar will consist of Updating Reports of:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>the International Chernobyl Project and an ongoing IAEA project on "One Decade After Chernobyl: Environmental Impact Assessment";
<LI>the WHO Conference on the "Health Consequences of the Chernobyl and other Radiological Accidents", including results of the IPHECA programme;
<LI>the "First International Conference of the European Union, Belarus, Russian Federation and Ukraine on the Consequences of the Chernobyl Accident", including the results of the Chernobyl programmes of the European Commission, Belarus, Russia and Ukraine; and,
<LI>relevant activities of UNESCO, UNSCEAR, FAO, and OECD/NEA.
</UL>
<P>
It is expected that summary reports of major bilateral projects will also be presented.
<P>
<STRONG>
TECHNICAL SYMPOSIUM
</STRONG>
<P>
The Technical Symposium will comprise:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Eight distinct Topical Sessions covering the major Conference topics; these will be based on scientific background papers prepared in advance by committees of senior scientists;
<LI>A Poster Session in which the individual papers submitted to the Conference will be displayed and discussed; and
<LI>A Concluding Session where the technical conclusions and recommendations of the Symposium will be summarized by the Conference President.
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
Topical Sessions
</STRONG>
<P>
The Background Papers  on each of the Conference topics will be prepared - under the auspices of the Joint Secretariat - by committees of senior experts, including experts from Belarus, the Russian Federation and the Ukraine, nominated by the Advisory Committee.  The background papers will be issued as "Pre-proceedings" of the Conference and distributed to participants in advance.  They will serve as a basis for discussion at the Topical Sessions.
<P>
At each Topical Session, the Rapporteur will introduce the relevant background paper and any related scientific papers presented at the Poster Session.  This will be followed by an open discussion.  After the discussion, the session Chairperson will draw up conclusions and recommendations.  The conclusions and recommendations for each Topical Session will be reported by the Rapporteur to the Bureau of the President and summarized by the President at the Final Session of the Technical Symposium.  These will serve as an input to the subsequent Opinion Formers' Session and the Decision Makers' Forum.
<P>
The topical sessions are as follows:
<P>
Topical Session 1: Clinically observed effects
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<UL>
<LI>the definitive numbers and the severity of the deterministic effects; and
<LI>results and conclusions of studies on occupationally exposed workers (including the emergency workers known as liquidators), covering both doses received and effects incurred (including diagnosis, attributability to radiation as cause, treatment and longer term follow-up).
</UL>
<P>
Topical Session 2:  Thyroid effects
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<UL>
<LI>the best estimates of thyroid dose distribution by area and age, and their accuracy;
<LI>effects of radiation on thyroid function;
<LI>spontaneously occurring thyroid effects and their reporting, diagnosis, treatment and follow-up;
<LI>pathology and molecular characterization of thyroid cancers;
<LI>definitive estimates of thyroid cancer in children and adults in Belarus, Ukraine and the Russian Federation;
<LI>attributability of thyroid effects to radiation doses and confounding factors;
<LI>conclusions of epidemiological studies; and
<LI>estimated future effects.
</UL>
<P>
Topical Session 3:  Longer term health effects
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<UL>
<LI>methods of dose reconstruction and their accuracy, and whole body measurements;
<LI>best estimates of dose distribution by area and age, and their accuracy;
<LI>epidemiological and theoretical estimates of induction of malignancies and hereditary disorders  numbers and severity and time profile, including effects among liquidators;
<LI>results of current studies (effects and non-effects), spontaneous effects, confounding factors;
<LI>likely capabilities and limitations of  epidemiological studies to accurately detect and quantify effects;
<LI>optimisation of long term follow-up; and
<LI>likely impact of countermeasures  past and proposed. 
</UL>
<P>
Topical Session 4:  Other health related effects: psychological consequences, stress, anxiety
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<UL>
<LI>psychological consequences among the population and emergency workers, clinical diagnosis and treatment;
<LI>mental distress and anxiety attributed to the accident directly or indirectly through perception of the level of contamination,  the countermeasures taken (evacuation, resettlement, agricultural countermeasures, etc.), the risk of other accidents and other factors;
<LI>perception of hazard from initial exposures compared with that from long term contamination; and
<LI>alleviation of psychological effects.
</UL>
<P>
Topical Session 5:  Consequences for the environment
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<UL>
<LI>effects of radiation versus those of countermeasures;
<LI>effects on flora and fauna and changes to ecosystems due to radiation and/or countermeasures, risk of genetic damage;
<LI>effects on agriculture, forestry, hunting and fisheries;
<LI>elevated concentrations of radionuclides in environmental media, including drinking water,h ot spots and hot particles;
<LI>secondary air contamination (resuspension from fires, surface water and soil);
<LI>migration of radionuclides;
<LI>potential for hazards to public health and risk to workers (e.g. agricultural, forestry and industrial workers);
<LI>likely development of relaxation of countermeasures;
<LI>management of contaminated territories, limitations for future use;
<LI>prospects for the 30km exclusion zone;
<LI>criteria for a return to normal, safety of continued residence; and
<LI>prognosis for the future.
</UL>
<P>
Topical Session 6:  Social, economic, institutional and political impact
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<UL>
<LI>changes in lifestyles and social framework;
<LI>treating long term health effects in changing social welfare systems;
<LI>effects of government fiscal policies with regard to subsidies and compensation;
<LI>industrial development and employment aspects;
<LI>changes in regulatory organization, standards and their enforcement;
<LI>interaction with general political change in countries of the former USSR;
<LI>perception of nuclear power, environmental concerns; and
<LI>international co-operation.
</UL>
<P>
Topical Session 7: Nuclear safety remedial measures
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<UL>
<LI>improvements in nuclear safety triggered by the accident;
<LI>overview of the results of the IAEA extrabudgetary programme; and
<LI>overview of the results of the EC Consortium Project.
</UL>
<P>
Topical Session 8: The Consequences in perspective: Prognosis for the future, the Chernobyl sarcophagus
<P>
The topics to be addressed at this session include:
<UL>
<LI>comparison of the radiation exposures from the accident with those due to natural background radiation;
<LI>comparison of numbers of attributable effects with those for other accidents and other technological and natural disasters, and with other risks to health common in everyday life, the question of attributability;
<LI>other public health concerns in countries of the former USSR;
<LI>future development of predicted effects, and
<LI>state and prospects of the Chernobyl sarcophagus.
</UL>
<P>
<STRONG>
Poster Sessions
</STRONG>
<P>
Posters of accepted individual papers will be exhibited in a Poster Hall and individually discussed with authors in two Poster Sessions  The full papers will be published in the Conference Proceedings. The Poster Hall will be open during the entire Conference and visits will be encouraged.
<P>
<STRONG>
Concluding Session 
</STRONG>
<P>
At a Concluding Session, the technical conclusions and recommendations of the Technical Symposium will be summarized by the Conference President.
<P>
<STRONG>
OPINION FORMERS' SESSION
</STRONG>
<P>
The Opinion Formers' Session will provide an opportunity for senior representatives of the information media to discuss the public's perception of the accident's consequences.  The Session will be followed by a press conference.
<P>
<STRONG>
DECISION MAKERS' FORUM
</STRONG>
<P>
The Decision Makers' Forum will conclude the Conference.  At three Panel Sessions, the social, economic and political aspects of decision making will be discussed by senior policy makers, taking into account the conclusions and recommendations of the Technical Symposium.
<P>
<STRONG>
CLOSING
</STRONG>
<P>
A Closing Session will conclude the Conference.  It will include:
<P>
<UL>
<LI>a farewell address on behalf of the United Nations by the UNDHA; and
<LI>the Conference President's keynote closing remarks and keynote statements presenting the final Conclusions and Recommendations of the Conference.
</UL>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
PRECEDING INTERNATIONAL MEETING
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
An International Meeting on the Safety of Chernobyl is being organized by the IAEA in co-operation with the UNDHA in the week preceding the conference.  The meeting will review the remedial measures taken since the accident to improve the safety of Chernobyl type reactors and the Chernobyl containment structure (the sarcophagus) built over the destroyed reactor.  The Meeting's conclusions and recommendations will serve as a basis for a background paper for sessions 7 and 8 of the Conference's Technical Symposium.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER> 
<STRONG>
REPORTING TO THE FOLLOWING IRPA CONGRESS
</CENTER>
</STRONG>
<P>
The Conference President will have the results of the Conference, including its conclusions and recommendations, reported to the international professional community of radiation protection specialists that will meet at the 1996 International Congress on Radiation Protection, IRPA9, to be held by the International Radiation Protection Association (IRPA) in the Hofburg Congress Centre in Vienna during the week following the Conference.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
PROCEEDINGS
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The IAEA will publish Proceedings of the Conference, including the welcoming remarks and opening addresses, the President's keynote speech, the updating reports, the background papers, the individual papers, Rapporteurs' and Chairpersons' reports for each session, the farewell address and the closing statement of the President highlighting the conclusions and recommendations of the Conference.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER> 
<STRONG>
WORKING LANGUAGES
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
Working languages of the Conference will be English, French, Russian and Spanish.  All communications, synopses, and papers must be sent to the Joint Secretariat in one of these languages.
<P>
Simultaneous interpretation may be provided between all the working languages if six weeks before the meeting it is seen from the Participation Forms received that this is required.
<P>
Please note that there will be no interpretation during poster sessions.
<P>
<HR> 
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
SECRETARIAT
</CENTER>
</STRONG>
<P>
The Joint Secretariat with the support of a Scientific Secretariat will serve the Conference. Assistance in the organization of the Conference will be provided by IAEA Conference Service Section, Division of External Relations.
<P>
The address of the Joint Secretariat is:
<P>
<CENTER>
c/o International Atomic Energy Agency<BR>
IAEA-CN-63<BR>
Vienna International Centre<BR>
Wagramerstrasse 5<BR> 
P.O. Box 100<BR>
A-1400 Vienna
<P>
Telephones:<BR>
+(43) (1) 2060 22729 (for enquiries about technical matters)<BR>
+(43) (1) 2060 21312 (for enquiries about administrative matters)
<P>
Telefax:<BR> 
+43 (1) 20607
<P>
AustriaCable:<BR>
INATOM VIENNA
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
<A HREF=call.html>CALL FOR PAPERS</A>
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
Technical experts, opinion formers, representatives of the scientific media, and officials in decision making positions in the areas of occupational and public health, environmental protection and nuclear safety from the Member States of the sponsoring organizations are invited to submit scientific papers to the Conference. They can contribute with any previously unpublished individual papers on the Conference topics and on related themes which could not be accommodated in the two prior Conferences or in the prior International Meeting.  Interested contributors are invited to submit extended synopses of about 1000 words, typed, in English, French, Spanish or Russian to the Joint Secretariat for review by the Advisory Committee.  Summaries should be sent to the competent official authority for transmission to the Joint Secretariat for the International Conference "One Decade after Chernobyl: Summing Up the Consequences of the Accident", c/o International Atomic Energy Agency, P.O. Box 100, A-1400 Vienna, Austria. Accepted papers shall be submitted in full and presented as a POSTER.  The full paper will be published in the Conference Proceedings.  The posters will be exhibited in the Poster Hall and discussed at the poster sessions.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
KEY DATES
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The deadline for submission of the Form for Submission of a Paper/Poster to the Joint Secretariat is 15 October 1995.
<P>
Notification of acceptance or rejection of extended synopses will be given by 30 November 1995.
<P>
The deadline for submission of full papers is 31 January 1996.  The posters shall be available on the first day of the Conference.  Further details concerning the full papers and posters will be sent to authors in due course.
<P>
For further information please contact the IAEA Conference Services Section (Fax no. +43-1-20607).
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
APPLICATIONS
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
The Participation Forms and, if applicable, the Forms of Submission of a Paper/Poster  which are enclosed  should be completed and sent as soon as possible through the competent official authority of a Member State (e.g. Ministry of Foreign Affairs) of one of the co-sponsoring organizations for subsequent transmission to the Joint Secretariat.  A participant will only be accepted if the Participation Form is transmitted through the above channels or by an organization invited to participate.
<P>
Detailed information on further arrangements, including accommodation, will be sent to all officially designated participants three months in advance of the Conference. 
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
THERE IS NO CONFERENCE FEE.
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
