</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
GC(39)/5
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<STRONG>
GC(39)/5<BR>
August 1995
</STRONG>
<P>
<CENTER>
<STRONG>
Introduction to the Agency's Accounts for 1994
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>
<CENTER>
<I>Excerpt from document GC(39)/5</I>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<OL>
<LI>I present herewith the Agency's accounts for the year ended 31 December 1994.  Part I contains the External Auditor's report to the Board of Governors on the audit of the accounts. The Agency's accounts, comprising Statements I to V and Schedules A to G, are presented in Parts II and III respectively. Part IV, entitled "Notes to the financial statements", describes the purpose and financing of the various Funds and the authority under which they are administered, and the significant accounting policies applied by the Secretariat in preparing the statements and schedules. In addition, the notes offer the reader information about significant items and events which could have a bearing on the financial position of the Agency or on the Funds under its control.
<P>
<LI>The presentation of the accounts has been changed in a number of areas where the Secretariat considered that the changes would enhance their information value to Member States. Some changes are also a direct response to the new accounting standards of the United Nations system. More substantial changes may be expected in the future, and after completion of the work of the Consultative Committee on Administrative Questions (CCAQ) Working Group on Financial Statements, which is formulating minimum standards for the presentation of financial statements, schedules and notes which could be recommended for use by all organizations of the United Nations system.
<P>
<LI>Significant changes made this year in the form and contents of the statements, schedules and notes are explained below: 
<P> 
(a) Statements III.B and IV.B show extrabudgetary contributions received, comparing them with the amounts originally expected. In previous years, the amounts shown were those received during the year for which they were pledged; amounts received later were excluded. In order to give equal recognition to Member States for all extrabudgetary contributions, these have been included regardless of when they were pledged.
<P>
(b) In previous years, Statements III.D, IV.D and V.2 showed extrabudgetary and trust fund contribution receivables as assets, and identical offsetting reserves as corresponding liabilities. Since the resources in the extrabudgetary and trust funds are kept on a cash basis, the receivables and the corresponding reserves have been removed from the balance sheets because cash basis accounting does not require the inclusion of accounts receivable in balance sheets.
<P>
(c) In previous years, Statement IV.A presented figures relating to Regional Co-operative Agreement (RCA) activities in a separate line. However, since RCA activities fall under the headings "Technical Co-operation", "Food and Agriculture, "Human Health" and "Nuclear Safety", the figures relating to them are this year reflected under these headings.
<P>
(d) Statements V.l and V.2 showing trust fund activities have been summarized this year. The three existing trust funds - the Research Institutes Trust Fund, the Technical Assistance and Co-operation Fund in Trust and the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor-Engineering Design Activities (ITER EDA) Trust Fund - are now shown in one line each. Full details regarding each research contract and project are available to the trustors.
<P>
(e) Schedule C.2 of the Agency's accounts for 1993 (GC(XXXVIII)/4), a summary of total income and expenditure for the latest complete budget year, has been discontinued. However, the information is available for internal management use.
<P>
(f) A schedule entitled "Administrative Fund - Regular Budget Summary by Item of Expenditure" has been added as Schedule G. The information contained in it is presented in greater detail in the "Report on Programme and Budgetary Performance in 1994" being issued separately under cover of a Note by the Secretariat.
<P>
<LI>The present position of the Agency with regard to the new accounting standards of the United Nations system is explained in Part IV (Note 2(k)).
<P>
<LI>Statement I.A.l shows an amount of $ 13 468 800 in respect of 1994 deferred programme activities which may be implemented in 1995. The extent to which 1993 deferred programme activities were implemented in 1994 is shown in Statement I.A.2; an unused balance of $ 3 446 190 was credited to the 1993 cash surplus. The extent to which 1992 deferred programme activities were implemented in 1994 is shown in Statement I.A.3; an unused balance of $ 1 329 686 was also credited to the 1993 cash surplus.  
<P> 
<LI>The budget year 1993 closed with a final cash surplus of $ 7 490 780, as shown in Statement I.C. Member States' individual shares in this surplus are shown in Schedule C.  As decided by the Board of Governors in June 1994, this cash surplus will be retained until the existence of arrears of contributions ceases to have a major detrimental impact on programme implementation, but in any case not later than 1997, or until otherwise decided by the Board (GOV/2734, Annex 4).
<P>
<LI>Statements IV.C and IV.D each include one new account: Indonesia- to administer a voluntary contribution of money to the Agency in support of Regional Co-operative Agreement (RCA) activities.
</OL>
<P>
(signed) HANS BLIX<BR>
Director General
