<P>
<CENTER>
<H4>
Communication of 8 September 1995 Received from the Permanent Mission of the Philippines to the International Atomic Energy Agency
</H4>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
1. On 8 September 1995, the Director General received a communication dated also 8 September 1995 from the Permanent Mission of the Philippines transmitting a Statement of 6 September 1995 by the President of the Republic of the Philippines concerning the resumption of nuclear testing by France.
<P>
2. As requested by the Permanent Mission of the Philippines, the text of the Statement is being circulated as an official document for the forthcoming regular session of the General Conference.
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<I>
Attachment
</I>
<P>
<CENTER>
<B>
Statement of H.E. President Fidel V. Ramos on the Nuclear Test by France
</B>
</CENTER>
<P>
I am profoundly disappointed by the news that France, in utter disregard of the concern expressed by many countries and ignoring the appeals of the countries that stand to be directly affected by its action, proceeded with its first nuclear test at the Mururoa Atoll.
<P>
France has dealt a serious blow to the cause of nuclear disarmament and has severely damaged the credibility of the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty which was extended indefinitely last May.
<P>         
The Philippines is committed to nuclear disarmament and is firmly opposed to the conduct of any nuclear tests, conscious of the serious medium and long-term environmental and human costs. I have repeatedly appealed to President Chirac to reconsider and cancel the planned tests. I am deeply saddened that he has not heeded my, and other leaders' appeal.
<P>         
France served as a beacon when it led other nuclear weapons States in observing the moratorium on nuclear testing. Now, France has deeply disillusioned the international community by turning its back on its previous restraint and proceeding with the tests.
<P>
The Philippines will sustain its initiatives in leading the Group of 77 at international and regional fora to protest nuclear testing by any nation. We again call on France to respect international opinion and heed the concerns expressed by countries in the Pacific Rim, which are most vulnerable to such tests by altogether canceling the remaining tests.
<P>
06 September 1995.<BR>
Manila
<P>
<HR>
<P>
</BODY>
</HTML>         
