<HTML>
<HEAD>         
<TITLE>
GC(39)/INF/25
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>
GC(39)/INF/25<BR>
20 September 1995
<BR>
Agenda Item 20
</STRONG>
<P>         
<CENTER>         
<H4>
Measures Against Illicit Trafficking in Nuclear Materials and other Radioactive Sources
</H4>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>         
The statement by the President of the Republic of Kazakhstan, Mr. N.A. Nazarbaev, which is reproduced overleaf is being circulated at the request of the Permanent Mission of the Republic of Kazakhstan.
<P>
<HR>       
<P>         
<CENTER>         
<STRONG>
STATEMENT<BR>
BY<BR>
THE PRESIDENT OF THE REPUBLIC OF KAZAKHSTAN,<BR>
MR. N.A. NAZARBAEV
</CENTER>
</STRONG>
<P>                           
September 1995
<P>         
Kazakhstan shares the concern of the world community and the Secretary-General of the United Nations, Mr. Boutros Boutros-Ghali, at the illicit trafficking in nuclear materials which is continuing despite the fact that the States-parties to the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT) have taken the decision to extend the Treaty indefinitely.
<P>    
The danger of proliferation is also heightened by the dismantling of large quantities of nuclear weapons, the activities of non-governmental bodies seeking to acquire nuclear devices and the risk of nuclear materials and weapons finding their way into regions where national and ethnic conflicts are taking place.
<P>
We support the efforts of the International Atomic Energy Agency to resolve this problem. Now that Kazakhstan has ratified the agreement with the Agency for the application of safeguards in connection with the NPT, it has joined the international safeguards system for preventing the proliferation of nuclear weapons and their components.
<P>
However, technical measures alone are no panacea against nuclear proliferation, since the activities of non-governmental elements pose a very great threat on account of their covert nature. A new climate of openness and transparency in nuclear matters is necessary.  The effectiveness of the non-proliferation regime depends on a high level of political commitment to international security by governments, which must co-operate to establish a tougher system of export monitoring and control. In this connection the proposal by Boris Yeltsin, President of the Russian Federation, for a meeting in spring 1996 to discuss nuclear security could be an important step towards uniting forces against illicit trafficking in nuclear materials.
<P>
<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT20-B02-141</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA060-000326-B021-100</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://nesihp01.iaea.or.at:80/GC/gc39inf26.html 193.81.60.210 19970115021850 text/html 2995
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 02:18:57 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Fri, 22 Sep 1995 12:13:25 GMT
Content-length: 2821
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>         
<TITLE>
GC(39)/INF/26
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>
GC(39)/INF/26<BR>
20 September 1995
</STRONG>
<BR>
<STRONG>
Agenda Item 15
</STRONG>
<P>         
<CENTER>         
<H4>
Measures to Strengthen International Co-Operation in<BR>
Nuclear Safety, Radiological Protection and<BR>
Radioactive Waste Management
</H4>
<P>
<HR>                           
<P>                           
<STRONG>
WRITTEN STATEMENT BY THE REPUBLIC OF AZERBAIJAN
</STRONG>
</CENTER>
<P>                           
The written statement by the Republic of Azerbaijan */ set out overleaf is being circulated at the request of the delegation of the Republic of Azerbaijan.
<P>
<HR>
<P>         
<CENTER>
<STRONG> 
WRITTEN STATEMENT BY THE REPUBLIC OF AZERBAIJAN
</CENTER>
</STRONG>                           
<P>                           
The Republic of Azerbaijan has no nuclear power plants or nuclear reactors.  However, providing radiation protection for the population and isolating people from the action of ionizing radiation are urgent problems for Azerbaijan.
<P>         
This is due largely to the fact that natural radiation background levels are increasing everywhere on earth as a consequence of human technological activities. However, the main threat of radioactive contamination of the environment in our region comes from the Medzamor nuclear power plant in neighbouring Armenia.
<P>         
This threat is due to its location in a seismic danger zone and also to the uncontrolled release of waste waters into a river flowing through the territory of Azerbaijan.
<P>         
This nuclear power plant, of the same type as the one at Chernobyl, is dangerous.  Prolonged mothballing has aggravated the threat posed by its operation. Starting up the Medzamor nuclear power plant will inevitably have a negative influence on the ecological situation not only in Azerbaijan, but throughout the region. The probability of an accident at the power plant is so great that the entire region will be on the brink of catastrophe while it is in operation.
<P>    
On 26 September 1995 the Armenian authorities intend to resume operation of this nuclear power plant, despite objections raised by many States.
<P>
The IAEA has never taken any decision to the effect that the Medzamor nuclear power plant is safe in terms of its technical parameters. We believe that the IAEA, as an authoritative international organization, should intensify its controls and its influence throughout the Southern Caucasus region. The Republic of Azerbaijan hopes that this esteemed organization, recognizing the full extent of the danger of operating the Medzamor nuclear power plant, will take all steps available to it to prevent its startup in order to avert disaster.
<P>
<HR>
<B>*/</B> Not a Member of the Agency
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
