<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> 
Statement by the UNSG
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H3>Message of the Secretary-General  Boutros Boutros-Ghali<BR>
to the Thirty-Ninth Regular Session of the
General Conference<BR>
of the International Atomic Energy Agency</H3>
<I>Vienna, 18 September 1995</I>
</CENTER>
<P>
<HR>
<P>                                               
I extend my warmest greetings to the participants at this, the thirty-ninth General Conference of the International Atomic Energy Agency. You have a challenging agenda. You face issues of compelling global significance.
<P>
This year marks the fiftieth anniversary of the founding of the United Nations. Much has been achieved. There have been many accomplishments. Throughout the Organization's existence the potential for close cooperation among the different parts of the United Nations system has been an important source of strength. Cooperation between the International Atomic Energy Agency and other parts of the United Nations system has been especially close and productive. These relationships must continue to be strengthened.
<P>
Amidst the many uncertainties of the post-Cold War era.  international peace, security, and development require that the international community give issues of nuclear control and nuclear safety the very highest priority. The world can take comfort from the fact that we are no longer standing at the edge of a nuclear precipice. But now is no time to rest. The stakes remain high. And time is not on our side.
<P>
The agenda is long. The items are compelling. Urgent priorities include preventing the further spread of nuclear weapons. halting nuclear testing, improving verification capabilities, stopping the illicit traffic in nuclear and other radioactive materials, banning the production of fissile materials for explosive devices, guaranteeing the safe disposal of radioactive wastes, and ensuring the continued safe and peaceful use of nuclear energy and related technologies.
<P>
The Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) is the cornerstone of international efforts to prevent the spread of nuclear weapons. Full adherence to the Treaty by all States is essential to international peace and security. It is our best hope for a world free of nuclear weapons.
<P>
I welcome tho positive results that were achieved at the Review and Extension Conference on the Non-Proliferation Treaty which took place earlier this year in New York. The indefinite extension of the Treaty has sent a needed signal. The decision to enhance the review process for the Treaty will help to strengthen internatlonal commitments. The agreements on Principles and Objectives for Nuclear Non-Proliferation and Disarmament are an important and useful step forward.
<P>
The NPT Conference set 1996 as the target date for the conclusion of a Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty. A majority of the international community view a complete ban on nuclear testing as a prerequisite for further progress towards non-proliferation and the eventual elimination of all nuclear weapons. Under the auspices of the United Nations in Geneva, negotiations are now proceeding on a comprehensive test ban treaty. I urge all participants to re-double their efforts. I appeal to all States to voluntarily refrain from nuclear testing, and to demonstrate to the world their commitment to a future free of nuclear weapons.
<P>
The NPT Conference also called for an early conclusion of an agreement to ban the production of fissile materials for nuclear weapons or other nuclear explosive devices. Such an agreement would be a significant contribution to nuclear non-proliferation. I call for the immediate commencement and early concluslon of negotiations on such an agreement.
<P>
In a recent letter, the Security Councll expressed its continued full support for the work being done by the IAEA and others to combat illicit trafficking in nuclear and other radioactive materials. I urge the Agency to examine ways in which it can further assist Member States in meeting their obligations. The international community will need to be far more vigilant than it has been if this menace is to be controlled.
<P>
In promoting international peace and security, full and mutually supportive cooperation between the Security Council and the IAEA will, as in the past, continue to be essential. The Agency's ongoing monitoring and verification activities in Iraq -- conducted in furtherance of Security Council resolutions -- demonstrate both the need and the importance of such cooperation.
<P>
I am pleased to note that since my last statement to you at the thirty-eighth session of the General Conference, there have been important developments in the implementation of IAEA safeguards in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK). The Agency and the DPRK have held extensive technical discussions relating to safeguards.  These are positive developments.
<P>
I welcome the Agency's efforts to strengthen its safeguards system, including its capacity to detect undeclared nuclear activities.  Verification is critical to an effective non-proliferation regime. Without effective verification there can be no firm basis for confidence. I pledge the continued active support of the United Nations for steps to strengthen the Agency's safeguards system. I urge all States to give their full support, including financial support, to these efforts.
<P>
The further development of nuclear applications in a wide variety of peaceful fields, and the IAEA's work related to the implementation of Agenda 21 and other development initiatives underline the broad mandate of the Agency, and why it is such an important part of the United Nation's family.
<P>
The IAEA will continue to have important international responsibilities in dealing with nuclear safety, radioactive waste management, and radiological protection. I urge Member States to ratify the Nuclear Safety Conventlon without delay, and to facilitate its early entry into force. I also urge all Member States who are in a position to do so to contribute actively to the development of the proposed Convention on the Safe Management of Radioactive Waste, and to participate in the work of the Standing Committee on Liability for Nuclear Damage.
<P>
In addressing the compelling challenges of global peace, security, and development, we can succeed only if we all work together. I pledge to you my full support for your efforts. I reaffirm my strong commitment to maintaining the close collaboration that has come to characterize the relationship between the IAEA and the United Nations. There is much to be done. Let us continue to go forward together.
<P>
Thank you.
<P>
<HR>
