<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> 
Statement by the Incoming President
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H3>Opening Statement by H.E. Mr. Chuchai Kasemsarn,<BR>
President of the thirty-ninth regular session of the General Conference of the International Atomic Energy Agency</H3>
<I> Vienna, 18 September 1995</I>
</CENTER>
<HR> 
<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC=/GC/images/thai.gif>
</CENTER>
<P>
<I>Excellencies, Distinguished Delegates, Mr. Director-General, Ladies and Gentlemen,</I>
<P>
At the outset, I would like to express to all of you my sincere appreciation for the honour which you have conferred upon Thailand by unanimously electing me as President of the thirty-ninth regular session of the General Conference of the IAEA. I wish, in particular, to thank the Ambassador of Australia for proposing my candidature on behalf of the SEAP Group to which Thailand belongs and the distinguished representatives of other regional groups for supporting my candidature.
<P>
I am taking up this high office with a sense of humility. I am aware of the increasingly important role that the Agency has been called upon to assume in our rapidly changing world. I shall do my utmost to ensure the success of this Conference. I am confident that I will receive full cooperation and support from all delegations and the Secretariat in carrying out this responsibility.
<P>
May I take this opportunity, on behalf of the General Conference, to express sincere thanks and appreciation to Prof. Alec Jean Baer of Switzerland who, as President, had ably performed and led the thirty-eighth regular session of the General Conference to a successful conclusion. Being his neighbour in the Board room during the past three sessions of the Board of Governors, I have come to value his wise counsels on various issues relating to the Agency s work.
<P>
<I>Excellencies, Distinguished Delegates,</I>
<P>
The convening of the thirty-ninth regular session of the General Conference coincides with the year of the fiftieth anniversary of the dropping of the first atomic bomb.  Its devastating effect should have convinced mankind not to ever again let history repeat itself. 25 years later the NPT was born and last May the Treaty was extended indefinitely with a view to preventing nuclear proliferation, enhancing the peaceful uses of nuclear energy and achieving nuclear disarmament. The world took note of the commitment made by nuclear-weapon States to pursue in good faith negotiations on effective measures relating to nuclear disarmament and to conclude a universal and internationally and effectively verifiable Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty no later than 1996.
<P>
I> Excellencies, Distinguished Delegates,</I>
<P>
Since the last General Conference, we have witnessed significant progress and developments in the Agency s activities. With regard to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons, past events have demonstrated the need for IAEA safeguards system to provide credible assurances not only on declared nuclear activities but also of the absence of undeclared nuclear activities. Consequently, the work of the Agency to further strengthen the effectiveness and improve the cost-efficiency of safeguards system has been endorsed in a comprehensive set of measures in Programme 93+2. I believe distinguished delegates would join me in commending the Director-General and his staff in this regard.  With respect to the peaceful uses of nuclear energy, the Agency has been the principal international instrument for promoting nuclear co-operation and the transfer of nuclear technology for peaceful purposes to developing countries. The areas of activities include: food irradiation, radiation protection, nuclear safety and radioactive waste management and the establishment of a Standing Advisory Group on Technical Assistance and Co-operations (SAGTAC). The continuation and further improvement in such activities require strong commitment by Member States in terms of adequate and predictable resources and implementation support to match the Agency s effort.
<P>
<I>Excellencies, Distinguished Delegates,</I>
<P>
My predecessor, in his last year's opening statement, said that applications of nuclear energy have transformed our world irreversibly. He also said that -- it is we who decided, under Article III of the Agency's Statute, to accelerate and enlarge the contribution of atomic energy to peace, health and prosperity throughout the world. I submit to all of you that in this post cold war era all of us should redouble our efforts to make the world a safer and better place to live in. The International Atomic Energy Agency, under the able leadership of Director-General Blix, could play a unique role not only in promoting and verifying the peaceful uses of nuclear energy but also in convincing the world at large of its positive contribution to the future of our children.
<P>
In conclusion, I make a renewed appeal for your co-operation and goodwill to ensure a successful outcome of this Conference.
<P>
Thank you.
<P>
<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
