Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 18 Sep 1995 13:26:05 GMT
Content-length: 5976
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> 
Statement by the Outgoing President
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<CENTER>
<H3>Statement by the Outgoing President, Prof. Alec Jean Baer,  to the<BR>
Opening of the 39th Session of the General Conference of the IAEA</H3>
<P>
<I>Vienna, 18 September 1995</I>
</CENTER>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC=/worldatom/images/baer.gif>
</CENTER>
<P>
Since the last session of our General Conference, the most prominent event in nuclear non-proliferation has been the indefinite extension of the Nuclear non-Proliferation Treaty.
<P>
This is a success, relative maybe, but a success all the same. It has been achieved in good part thanks to the great personal qualities of the president of the Conference, but also, and this is important, thanks to efforts by many delegations and by numerous participants who had been delegated to New York by States, the population of which does not want any nuclear armaments anymore.
<P>
 Assessing the role of our Agency, the Conference has been absolutely clear. It has emphasized that the IAEA plays a critical role in the application of the safeguards written in the NPT. It has recognized the importance, for the Agency, to be given the means to accomplish its task and it has called for application of the measures decided by the Board of Governors towards a strengthening of safeguards and a better detection of undeclared activities. In other words, it has placed this Agency where it belongs, that is at the hub of nuclear non-proliferation activities.
<P>
Turning to other aspects of this Agency's work, the Conference has specifically asked that it keep looking for reliable and predictable means to finance technical cooperation. Technical cooperation however is much more than a matter of finances. Even though, in Art.III of our Statute, it comes ahead of safeguards, its importance is by far not as considerable. As part of a long-term planning for the Agency, the purpose of technical cooperation must urgently be examined in view of the results achieved so far. When we are clear about what we want, we can discuss finances. Time is of the essence, however. For twenty years now the gap between amounts pledged and targets to be reached has been increasing systematically. The Board of Governors must tackle without delay what is about to become the question of the survival of technical cooperation.
<P>
In New York, the extension of the NPT was the main topic of the Conference, however, and more than 170 non-nuclear weapons states, almost 120 of which are members of this Agency, have found it in their interest to renounce forever the acquisition of nuclear weapons. They have done it because they believe that nuclear disarmament is bound to come. They have expressed this unfaltering hope through the adoption of a text requesting nuclear-weapons states to demonstrate utmost restraint in this regard and in expectation of the signature of a Comprehensive Test-ban Treaty in 1996. In so doing, they were asking nuclear-weapons states for a small encouraging sign, in exchange for the major commitment that they have now accepted for ever. It is regrettable that two states are rebuffing this request.
<P>
The renewed nuclear weapons tests this year are deeply disappointing.
<P>
The NPT Extension Conference may be a turning point in the history of non-proliferation, however. This Conference may still be too close for us to realize all its significance, but the extension of the NPT is not an isolated occurence. It belongs to a time of renewed interest for a Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty and for other initiatives aiming at a true and durable nuclear disarmament.
<P>
This renewed activity is not unique to non-proliferation. By contrast with over forty years of relative political stability that we have known after the Second World War, we are now in a period of rapid evolution and nobody knows yet how long it shall last or what its consequences shall be.
<P>
Nuclear non-proliferation is fast evolving.  It is obvious, however, that some are still clinging to ideas or to attitudes that might well have been acceptable thirty years ago, but that the great majority of us vigorously objects to today.  Those who cling to the past have but one alternative, a fast change of behaviour or extinction.  If history is any guide, it guarantees that most of them will go the way of the mammoths and of the dinosaurs. By contrast, those who have realized what is happening, those who are sufficiently down-to-earth to accept changes and to modify their paradigms accordingly are those who will survive. They shall define the rules of the new game. They shall make the revolution that will open another long period of stability.
<P>
Whether the IAEA wants it or not, it cannot escape this revolution. It is living through it.  Changes may not be very spectacular to the layman, but they are of a fundamental nature.  Take, for instance, the agenda for the session that we are opening this morning. You will find such topics as the strengthening of safeguards, their financing, that of technical assistance, and even amendments to Article Vl of the Statute. None of these topics is new, quite obviously.  They all smack of "deja vu", but what is new is that people are changing and attitudes are changing.
<P>
The climate of the discussions is different. A growing willingness to progress is at last in the air. There reigns a feeling that rapid improvements may be possible after all. The revolution is underway and shall not be stopped by anybody.
<P> 
If we do not wish our decisions to disappear like so many others in the obscurity of minutes of past meetings, let us forget the old thinking schemes. Let us show some enthusiasm for a novel approach to non-proliferation and let us be those who create the future rather than those who are enduring it. This future, our future, shall be built upon the lessons drawn from past mistakes and upon the hopes that we express for it to-day.
<P>
<HR>
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
