<html>

<head>
<title>NF - Guidelines for Mathematics</title>
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>

<body>
<p>% Select the entire text and paste it into a LaTeX document. Typeset.</p>
<p>\documentstyle{article}<br>
<br>
% use \bm{text} to get 'text' in boldmath style;<br>
% no matter if you are in math mode or not<br>
%<br>
\newcommand{\bm}[1]<br>
{\ifmmode<br>
\mbox{\boldmath$#1$}<br>
\else<br>
\boldmath$#1$\unboldmath<br>
\fi}<br>
<br>
\begin{document}</p>
<p>{\bf Guidelines~for~Mathematics:}~~Authors can assist our processing of manuscripts if they aim to approach the NF typesetting conventions for mathematics, 
which are as follows. </p>
<p>Scalar quantities are italic, with the exception of the base of natural logarithms and $\sqrt{-1}$, which are roman: ${\rm e}$ and ${\rm i}$. The names of standard 
mathematical functions are roman, thus:</p>
<p>$\ln (\exp x ) = x$, <br>
$\sin ( \sin ^{-1} y ) = y$,<br>
${\rm d}z^2 / {\rm d}z = 2 z$. </p>
<p>Use $\exp (\ldots)$ instead of ${\rm e}^{(\ldots)}$ except in the simplest cases. Subscripts and superscripts which refer to other mathematical quantities used in 
the paper are italic; otherwise they are roman. Therefore, the Kronecker delta is $\delta_{ij}$, while the electron plasma frequency is $\omega_{\rm pe}^2 = 
n_{\rm e} e^2/m_{\rm e} \epsilon_0 $. Complicated subscripts, particularly subscripts to subscripts, should not be used. Vector quantities are bold italic 
($\bm{E}$), and tensors are sanserif bold. The nabla symbol should be used for the differential vector operators grad, div and curl (rot): $\bm{E} = \bm{\nabla} 
\phi$; $\bm{\nabla} \cdot \bm{E} = \rho / \epsilon_0$; $\bm{B} = \bm{\nabla} \times \bm{A}$. </p>
<p>NF will try to set equations in the standard two column format, splitting equations across lines if necessary. Therefore, please construct equations to make the 
decision on splitting straightforward. Often a built-up fraction or a matrix is better formed of small components defined in other equations. </p>
<p>\end{document}</p>
</body>

</html>
