<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>
YEARBOOK 1995
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR=#ffffff>
<H2>
<CENTER>
The IAEA Yearbook
</CENTER>
</H2>
<P>
<HR>
<P>
<CENTER>
<B><I>
Foreword
<BR>
<I>by the Director General</I>
</I></B>
</CENTER>
<P>
The IAEA Yearbook 1995 concentrates on developments in nuclear
science and technology and on the work of the IAEA during the
previous year, but it also records major events which took place
during the early months of the current year. One such event was
the holding in New York of the Review and Extension Conference of
the Treaty on the Non-Proliferation of Nuclear Weapons (NPT). The
outcome of the conference was the extension, for an indefinite
period, of the treaty and hence, in particular, of the
obligations of the IAEA in the sphere of safeguards -- the system
of international inspection for verifying the exclusively
peaceful uses of nuclear energy. A background is provided in this
year's lead article.
<P>
Further details regarding recent changes and future developments
in IAEA safeguards are given in Part E of the Yearbook: the steps
already undertaken and the measures being implemented to improve
the cost effectiveness of safeguards and to increase the
assurance of the completeness of information on nuclear
activities in States which have undertaken not to acquire nuclear
weapons; and the new verification roles that the IAEA may be
called upon to play in support of international nuclear arms
control agreements.
<P>         
Article IV of the NPT recalls the right of all countries to have
access to the benefits of nuclear science and technology. The
IAEA has, since its inception, been engaged in the transfer of
knowledge and expertise in these areas. The introduction to Part
A of the Yearbook describes some of the new approaches now being
undertaken to ensure that these technology transfer activities
bring lasting benefit to end users as the concept of 'partnership
in development' is introduced. The accompanying article describes
the history of a particular aspect of the programme -- the
training courses organized over the past twenty years in the
areas of nuclear power and safety.
<P>            
The Statute of the IAEA defines one of its functions as being "to
encourage and assist research on, and development and practical
application of, atomic energy for peaceful uses throughout the
world." Part B of the Yearbook describes just a few of the IAEA
activities in this area: the use of nuclear techniques to help
maintain a cleaner environment, methods for improving animal
production and the use of research reactors for the production of
radioisotopes and for education and training purposes.
<P>         
Part C of the Yearbook as usual deals with the status and trends
in nuclear power, the nuclear fuel cycle and radioactive waste
management throughout the world, together with details of the
IAEA programmes in these areas. While there have been no
fundamental changes in the worldwide development of nuclear power
in recent years, its growth in southeast Asia has continued. It
is clear overall that nuclear power offers a viable option that
needs to be carefully considered in a situation where there is
increasing anxiety about the environmental problems caused by the
burning of fossil fuels.
<P>         
In the area of nuclear safety, the most significant developments
in 1994 were the opening for signature of the international
Convention on Nuclear Safety and the publication of the new
International Basic Safety Standards for Protection Against
Ionizing Radiation andfor the Safety of Radiation Sources. Both
of these events are described in Part D of the Yearbook, which
this year is issued in a new format concentrating on selected
topics of special interest. These range from the work being done
to ensure the integrity of nuclear power reactor steam generators
to the latest results on the mechanisms and genetics of tumour
induction.
<P>         
Finally, Part F once again provides reference material on the
structure and organization of the IAEA and its relationship with
its Member States.
<P>         
The celebration of the fiftieth anniversary of the United Nations
has focused renewed attention on the need for an effective and
efficient international system which is capable of meeting the
challenges of a changing agenda. The IAEA is well prepared, on
its part, to respond to such challenges and its programme
continues to evolve to take account of the new requirements of
its Member States. In this spirit, we are already looking ahead
and planning for the year 2000 and beyond.
<P>  
<HR>
<P>
