<title>About Keep America Beautiful, Inc.</title>
<meta name="KEYWORDS"
content="Keep America Beautiful, KAB, affiliate, community, education, litter, recycling">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><!--Source code written by Dawn Rosner. FrontPage required for upload, and has tampered with the original coding--></p>
<p><img src="kabbanr.gif" lowsrc="lkabbnr.gif"
alt="About Keep America Beautiful, Inc." align="bottom"
width="531" height="133"> </p>
<h3>About Keep America Beautiful, Inc.</h3>
<p>Keep America Beautiful, Inc. (KAB) is a non-profit, public
education and community improvement organization with local
affiliates throughout North America that is committed to
preserving the natural beauty, environment and resources of
America and improving waste handling at the community level. A
leader in <em><strong>litter prevention, community improvement</strong></em>
and <em><strong>beautification</strong></em> since its founding
in 1953, KAB is also a respected educator on solid waste and its
effective management. KAB's chief objective is the support and
enhancement of the quality of life in American communities
through a structured, systematic, <em>community-based</em> and <em>results-oriented</em>
program known as the KAB SYSTEM that helps communities prevent
litter, encourage community beautification and generate ongoing
support for integrated waste management. </p>
<p>Today, over 76 million Americans are <em>directly</em>
influenced annually by KAB and its almost 500 certified local
affiliate programs in 41 states. Millions more are influenced
indirectly by KAB national communications and programs. In the
early 1970's, KAB played a pivotal national role in raising
public awareness on the environment with its still
widely-recognized &quot;crying Indian&quot; public service
advertising campaign. However, KAB's most critical role through
the years has been that of encouraging Americans to get directly
involved voluntarily in a variety of environmental and community
improvement efforts. Over 2.6 million community volunteers took
part directly in KAB affiliate programs in 1995. </p>
<p>KAB advocates community-action on the environment, not
finger-pointing or blame- placing. The sum total of the
organization's effort is dedicated to facilitating partnerships
locally and nationwide that lead to accountable action on litter
and garbage at the community level. The KAB SYSTEM is the only
non-confrontational, community-wide social-change mechanism made
available to American communities and coordinated by a national
non profit organization. Each KAB community affiliate is locally
organized and operated. In 1995, two-thirds of the affiliates
were directly involved in solid waste planning in their
communities. Over 95% of affiliates are primary sources of
recycling education in their communities. </p>
<p>To retain affiliation with KAB, local affiliates must annually
certify the accountability of their activities in terms of
measurable progress made against a series of established
environmental and organizational objectives. The annual
certification of local affiliates ensures that the community uses
all elements of the KAB designed process that has been proven to
forge the kind of community-wide attitude and behavioral changes
and ongoing involvement of the citizenry that is the root of
environmental and social progress. These methods are building
blocks that give communities the kind of success experiences in
collaborative social endeavor that enables them to move on as
communities to tackling broader, more complex social and
environmental challenges. </p>
<p>On an everyday basis, KAB SYSTEM activities promote <em>quality
of life</em> along with environmental quality. In addition to
average litter reductions of 50 percent in their communities as a
result of KAB programs, many affiliates now also report crime
reductions in participating areas, increased community pride and
participation, and a significantly improved climate for economic
development. This progress is highly cost effective for the
communities involved as well. For every one dollar in public
money budgeted to KAB affiliate programs in 1995, an average of
$9.89 was returned to public treasuries in the form of
cost-avoidance, reduced clean up expenses, volunteer efforts
gained and goods and services donated by the private sector.<br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>A Few Current KAB National Initiatives</h3>
<dl>
    <dt><a href="bab.html"><strong>Build America Beautiful</strong></a><br>
    </dt>
    <dd>A national partnership with the National Association of
        Home Builders (NAHB) aimed at improving the performance
        of home builders, developers and contractors on litter
        prevention, site maintenance and solid waste issues such
        as source reduction, recycling (lumber, steel and other
        construction materials in addition to consumer materials)
        and in contractor/vendor education. Construction areas
        can be certified as BAB sites using a process designed
        jointly by KAB and NAHB and can enter a national
        Beautiful Builder awards program.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dt><a href="glad.html"><strong>GLAD Bag-a-Thon</strong></a><br>
    </dt>
    <dd>KAB and First Brands have teamed up to create the
        nation's biggest single clean-up event, the GLAD
        Bag-a-Thon. Millions of <em>tons</em> were collected by
        individual volunteers across the nation in the Bag-A-Thon
        last year. Bag-a-Thon is now in its tenth year.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dt><a href="loop.html"><strong>Close The Loop. Buy Recycled.</strong></a><br>
    </dt>
    <dd>A national partnership with the U.S. Environmental
        Protection Agency (EPA) aimed on educating consumers of
        the environmental contribution, price parity and
        performance parity of recycled, recyclable and
        recycled-content products.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dt><a href="nicad.html"><strong>Rechargeable Battery
        Recycling Program</strong></a><br>
    </dt>
    <dd>&quot;Charge Up To Recycle&quot; is a national
        partnership with the Rechargeable Battery Recycling
        Corporation (a coalition of battery manufacturers) aimed
        at national recycling of NiCd batteries (and eventually
        NiMh and others) through retail locations, community
        collection drives and commercial collection programs.
        Richard Karn (AL on ABC's <em>Home Improvement</em>) is
        national spokesman for the effort which launches this
        year.</dd>
    <dd>&#160;</dd>
    <dt><strong>Graffiti Hurts</strong><br>
    </dt>
    <dd>A national partnership with Sherwin-Williams and its
        Krylon brand to educate American communities about the
        poisonous effect graffiti can have on communities and
        about the ways communities can stop graffiti without
        confrontation. Several cities are now pioneering programs
        to empower neighborhoods to end graffiti vandalism for
        good. </dd>
</dl>
<p><em><strong>Also:</strong></em> Among hundreds of KAB programs
across the nation, others include a national major appliance
recycling program, a national box and container collection
program, education initiatives on a range of issues,
international initiatives to bring KAB-type approaches to
communities in need outside of the U.S. and many other product
recycling and collection initiatives. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
The bottom line? Through the national efforts of Keep America
Beautiful, Inc. and the KAB SYSTEM, citizens across America are
being energized to take an active role in caring for their
community and the environment. In doing so, they are gaining the
confidence to address other pressing environmental and social
challenges with similar success. Our programs influence millions
of Americans to put the environment on the top of their personal
and family agendas&#151;and gives them substantive ways to go out
and <em>actually do something about improving their community
environment</em> instead of pointing fingers or shouting about
it. </p>
<p>With the KAB SYSTEM, attitudes <em>are</em> changing.
Solutions to complex issues are being found. While litter
prevention and integrated solid waste management may not be given
headline status, their solutions provide the basic first steps
for enhancing the quality of life in America's communities. </p>
<p>For more information, <a href="mailto:keepamerbe@aol.com">e-mail</a>
our staff. </p>
<hr>
<p>Learn how to become a <a href="cert.html">KAB Affiliate
Community.</a> <br>
Return to <a href="index.html">Home Page</a>.</p>
