<html>
<head>
<title>Keep America Beautiful, Inc. - Material for Teachers</title>
<meta name="KEYWORDS"
content="Keep America Beautiful, KAB, teaching, teachers, curricula, curriculum, education, learning, environment, environmental">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><!--Source code written by Dawn Rosner. FrontPage required for upload, and has tampered with the original coding--></p>
<p><img src="applebnr.gif" lowsrc="lapplbnr.gif"
alt="Keep America Beautiful, Inc. - Material for Teachers"
align="bottom" width="531" height="133"> </p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h3>Where are the citizens and officials who will make tomorrow's
decisions about solid waste? They're in your classroom today.</h3>
<p>It's crucial that these future leaders understand waste issues
and how waste can be managed. There will always be garbage that
must be dealt with safely, even after recycling, composting, and
source reduction have done their part. <br>
</p>
<p>KAB's educational resources for teachers and students provide
a balanced perspective of waste and the options for its
management in clear and user-friendly formats.<br>
</p>
<p><img src="curric.gif" lowsrc="lcurric.gif"
alt="Curriculum Guides" align="right" hspace="0" width="258"
height="156"> Two curricula: <em>Waste In Place</em> for grades
K-6 and <em>Waste: A Hidden Resource</em> for grades 7-12, build
critical thinking, processing, and problem solving skills through
imaginative, hands-on lessons. Lessons can be taught individually
or in sequence.<br>
</p>
<p>Developed and field-tested by professional educators and waste
experts, the curricula are being used nationwide by thousands of
teachers to influence positive behavior, foster social
responsibility and respect for the environment, and enrich the
learning experience.</p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="wip"><em>Waste In Place</em></a></h3>
<p><a name="wip">Woody Woodpecker, the popular cartoon character
and KAB mascot, introduces students in grades K-6 to litter and
waste issues. This interdisciplinary curriculum has 37 lesson
plans grouped by subject. </a></p>
<p><a name="wip">Students learn about: </a></p>
<ul>
    <li><a name="wip">preventing litter </a></li>
    <li><a name="wip">managing solid waste </a></li>
    <li><a name="wip">source reduction </a></li>
    <li><a name="wip">recycling </a></li>
    <li><a name="wip">composting </a></li>
    <li><a name="wip">sanitary landfilling </a></li>
    <li><a name="wip">waste-to-energy incineration</a></li>
</ul>
<p><a name="wip">The hands-on format of each lesson encourages
critical thinking and process science skills and prepares
students for participation in community problem-solving.</a></p>
<p><a name="wip">Try the </a><a href="pizza.html"><strong>SAMPLE
LESSON</strong></a>, or <a href="mailto:kabusa@aol.com">e-mail
our Director of Education</a> for information on ordering or
attending a Teacher Training Workshop.</p>
<hr>
<h3><a name="wahr"><em>Waste: A Hidden Resource</em></a></h3>
<p><a name="wahr">The landfill in Center City has closed, and
it's up to your class to resolve issues causing environmental,
societal, and economic boundaries. </a></p>
<p><a name="wahr">The role-playing simulation is just one of 36
innovative, freestanding lesson plans in <em>Waste: A Hidden
Resource</em>. In it, students in grades 7-12 become citizens,
elected officials, environmentalists, and business leaders
gathering facts, making decisions, and examining the
consequences.</a></p>
<p><a name="wahr">Each lesson involves students in investigating
the sources, components and management of municipal solid waste
or hazardous waste. Using critical thinking and problem-solving
skills they explore how various options can work together to
safely manage waste and learn the importance of gaining
consensus.</a></p>
<p><a name="wahr">Concepts, background and time estimates for
each lesson plan are provided.</a></p>
<p><a name="wahr">You can view a </a><a href="sample2.html"><strong>SAMPLE
LESSON</strong></a>, or <a href="mailto:kabusa@aol.com">e-mail
our Director of Education</a> for information on ordering or
attending a Teacher Training Workshop.</p>
<hr>
<h3>Teacher Training</h3>
<p>Comprehensive training workshops introducing teachers to <em>Waste
In Place</em> and <em>Waste: A Hidden Resource</em> are
available. Professional trainers with educational backgrounds and
classroom experience combine interactive activities with lively
demonstrations to show you how to maximize the curricula's impact
and make a lasting impression on students.</p>
<p>With the trainer's help, every teacher performs lesson plans
during the one-day workshop to gain additional confidence.</p>
<p>Regional workshops are available through Keep America
Beautiful, Inc. and its state and local affiliates. For
additional information on teacher training, or if you have any
questions, please or <a href="mailto:kabusa@aol.com">e-mail our
Director of Education</a>.</p>
<p>For other useful items for the classroom, including posters,
videos, and more, please see our <a href="stuff.html">catalog</a>.</p>
<hr>
<p>Return to <a href="index.html">Home Page</a>.</p>
