<html>
<head>
<title>Keep America Beautiful, Inc. - Charge Up To Recycle</title>
<meta name="KEYWORDS"
content="Keep America Beautiful, NiCd, recycling, batteries, Charge Up To Recycle">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><!--Source code written by Dawn Rosner. FrontPage required for upload, and has tampered with the original coding--></p>
<p><img src="chrgbnr.gif" lowsrc="lchrgbnr.gif"
alt="Keep America Beautiful - Charge Up To Recycle"
align="bottom" width="531" height="133"> </p>
<p><em><strong>A Program of The Rechargeable Battery Recycling
Corporation Endorsed by Keep America Beautiful, Inc.</strong></em></p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h3>About the Program</h3>
<p>The Rechargeable Battery Recycling Corporation (RBRC) is a
national, nonprofit, public service organization designed to
administer the collection and recycling of rechargeable
Nickel-Cadmium (NiCd, or &quot;nikad&quot;) batteries. Recently,
RBRC launched the <em>Charge Up to Recycle! </em>campaign, which
is a nationwide education and mobilization program aimed at
establishing battery recycling strategies in three separate
areas:</p>
<blockquote>
    <p>The <em>Retail Recycling Plan</em> provides electronic
    retail stores, such as Radio Shack&#153; and Circuit
    City&#153;, with collection boxes that will enable the stores
    to serve as collection points for used NiCd batteries. The
    boxes themselves are preaddressed, and have prepaid shipping
    labels, so the retailer can easily ship the collected
    batteries for recycling.</p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p>The Community Recycling Plan assists counties and
    municipalities to establish household NiCd battery collection
    programs. </p>
</blockquote>
<blockquote>
    <p>Under the Business &amp; Public Agency Recycling Plan
    businesses and government agencies receive information on how
    to set up and operate a battery collection program in their
    offices, and are offered a blanket rate for shipping the used
    NiCds to the recycler. </p>
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Who Covers the Recycling Costs? </h3>
<p>The Rechargeable Battery Recycling Corporation (RBRC) pays to
have the batteries recycled by the International Metals
Reclamation Company, located in Pennsylvania. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>How are the Batteries Recycled? </h3>
<p>At the recycling facility, a thermal process is used to
reclaim the cadmium, nickel and iron content of the batteries.
The recycled cadmium is used to make new batteries while the
nickel and iron are used to make stainless steel. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>How is the Program Funded? </h3>
<p>RBRC has established the <em>RBRC Seal </em>as a standard for
battery labeling. License fees paid by rechargeable battery and
battery-powered product manufacturers, which permit them to place
the RBRC Seal on their products, fund the program. Currently,
over 200 companies have entered the license agreement. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Which States are Participating? </h3>
<p>The U.S. Congress recently passed a bill which states that
NiCd rechargeable batteries are exempt from hazardous waste
regulations even if commercially generated because viable means
now exist for these batteries to be recycled. As a result, RBRC
is launching its <em>Charge Up To Recycle!</em> campaign in all
50 states. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Are Other Batteries Accepted? </h3>
<p>The <em>Charge Up to Recycle!</em> program only handles NiCd
batteries at this point (and NOT Nickel Metal-Hydride [NiMh] or
any other kinds of rechargeable batteries). Mixed shipments will
be returned. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>How Do I Find Out Who is Participating in My Community? </h3>
<p>An 800 line has been established by RBRC to direct individuals
to the collection center nearest them. It is 1-800-8-BATTERY. </p>
<hr>
<p>Return to <a href="index.html">Home Page</a>. </p>
<p>Read the &quot;Charge Up To Recycle&quot; <a
href="pr-nicad.html">Press Release</a>. </p>
