<html>
<head>
<title>Keep America Beautiful, Inc. Affiliate Community
Certification</title>
<meta name="KEYWORDS"
content="Keep America Beautiful, KAB, affiliate, community, communities, litter, beautification, waste, trash, garbage, recycling, environment, environmental">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><!--Source code written by Dawn Rosner. FrontPage required for upload, and has tampered with the original coding--></p>
<p><img src="kabbanr.gif" lowsrc="lkabbnr.gif"
alt="How to Become a KAB Certified Affiliate" align="bottom"
width="531" height="133"> </p>
<h2>Why and How to Become a KAB Certified Affiliate Community</h2>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>The KAB System</h3>
<p>In nearly 500 cities, towns, and counties in America, litter
has been reduced, solid waste is being managed more effectively,
and people respect and care for the local environment. What makes
these communities unique? Keep America Beautiful, Inc. and the
KAB System.</p>
<p>The KAB System is a behavior-based approach to prevent
littering and improve waste handling practices at the grassroots
level through education, community-wide involvement, and
public-private partnerships. It is offered to communities on a
certification basis.</p>
<p>Becoming a KAB affiliate requires a commitment from citizens,
businesses, elected and public officials, and civic leaders to
work together in identifying local concerns and applying the
System's five-step approach: getting the facts, involving the
people, planning systematically, focusing on results, and
providing positive reinforcement.</p>
<p>The KAB System improves communities because it addresses the
foundations that cause waste to be mishandled and provides
long-term solutions, rather than focus on one-time cleanup
events.</p>
<p>Proven effective in communities of every size, the KAB System
can work in your community, too.</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<blockquote>
    <p><strong>Instilling Positive Attitudes&#151;</strong>The
    KAB System responds to the underlying norms people have that
    result in littered conditions: the belief that someone else
    will clean up after them; no sense of ownership; and that it
    is acceptable to litter where it has already accumulated.
    Using KAB's five-step attitude-change process, affiliate
    communities foster positive attitudes and reinforce the
    concept of citizen ownership of roads, parks, and other
    public lands. These steps are also used by KAB affiliates to
    address local solid waste management concerns.</p>
    <p><strong>Community Ownership&#151;</strong>The structure of
    a KAB affiliate ensures broad-based involvement of all
    sectors of the community and empowers a volunteer board of
    directors and subcommittees to mobilize citizens to action. </p>
    <p><strong>Standards of Performance&#151;</strong>Each KAB
    affiliate conducts two annual measurements to document
    improved waste handling in the community and the return on
    public monies invested in the program. A photographic survey
    objectively examines trends in litter accumulation in the
    community and uses a formula to calculate reductions in
    litter from year to year. A cost/benefit analysis measures
    the dollar value returned to the community in the form of
    cost-avoidance, reduced cleanup costs, volunteer hours, and
    donated goods and services for each $1 of municipal monies
    provided. </p>
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>National Initiatives</h3>
<p>Exciting program dimensions are developed by KAB in
partnership with corporate members and members of its National
Advisory Council. They include:</p>
<blockquote>
    <p><a href="loop.html"><strong>&quot;Close the Loop. Buy
    Recycled.&quot;</strong></a><strong>&#151; </strong>Keep
    America Beautiful affiliates are educating consumers and
    businesses about &quot;buying recycled&quot; with a turn-key
    kit created by KAB and the U.S. Environmental Protection
    Agency. Fifteen affiliates helped develop and field-test the
    kit.</p>
    <p><a href="glad.html"><strong>GLAD Bag-A-Thon</strong></a><strong>&#151;</strong>Over
    75 affiliates participate in this ongoing cleanup and
    recycling program, the largest of its kind in the U.S.
    Year-round educational actions culminate each spring in a
    GLAD Bag-A-Thon cleanup/recycling day or week in the
    affiliate's community. </p>
    <p><a href="bab.html"><strong>Build America Beautiful</strong></a><strong>&#151;</strong>All
    KAB affiliates can help home builders reduce job-site litter
    and waste with guidelines from KAB and the National
    Association of Home Builders. </p>
    <p><strong>RJ Reynolds/VANTAGE Brands portable ashtray
    program,</strong> to reduce cigarette litter, and the
    &quot;No Butts About It&quot; awards. Includes
    litter-awareness video &quot;How Did This Get Here?&quot; </p>
    <p><strong>Graffiti Hurts&#151;</strong>Keep America
    Beautiful, in partnership with The Sherwin-Williams Company
    and five KAB affiliates, field-tested graffiti-prevention
    approaches in creating an education kit to increase local
    understanding of graffiti. </p>
    <p><a href="nicad.html"><strong>NiCd Battery Recycling</strong></a>
    is being promoted by KAB and affiliates in cooperation with
    the Rechargeable Battery Recycling Corporation, to recover
    batteries from home electronics and tools. </p>
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Network Services</h3>
<p>Network services are provided to KAB affiliates so that they
serve their communities more effectively and maintain a
leadership role in litter and solid waste concerns.</p>
<blockquote>
    <p><strong>Field Counseling and Guidance&#151;</strong>Quarterly
    contacts with each affiliate are made by KAB staff and/or a
    National Representative. Calls offer support and guidance on
    all aspects of the KAB System and its use. Site visits by a
    National Representative may also be scheduled to provide
    training and counseling for an affiliate's coordinator and
    board of directors.</p>
    <p><strong>Workshops and Seminars&#151;</strong>Workshops may
    be held regionally, or for individual affiliates by a KAB
    National Representative. They include training in the use of
    KAB curricula, new coordinator training, risk communication,
    and the special Building Better Board Relationships&quot;
    seminar for an affiliate's board of directors. Take-away
    materials supplement each workshop. </p>
    <p><strong>Regional and Annual Meetings&#151;</strong>Regional
    and annual meetings are held by KAB to reach affiliate
    coordinators, their staffs, key board members, and the public
    and private sectors. Agendas for regional meetings include
    training sessions, professional skills development, case
    studies, and workshops on solid waste and litter issues.
    National trends and issues, as well as KAB's National Awards
    ceremony, highlight the annual meeting. </p>
    <p><strong>Media Relations&#151;</strong>KAB's Communications
    Department helps strengthen an affiliate's local media
    relations through public service advertising and other
    strategies. </p>
    <p><strong>Informational Mailings&#151;</strong>KAB, in
    cooperation with member companies or members of its National
    Advisory Council, provides publications, videos, and other
    educational material. </p>
    <p><a href="awards.html"><strong>National Awards Program</strong></a><strong>&#151;</strong>Each
    year, over 80 prestigious awards are given by KAB to
    recognize outstanding KAB affiliates, civic and youth groups,
    individuals, and companies. </p>
    <p><strong>Monthly issues of </strong><em><strong>Network</strong></em><strong>&#151;</strong><em>Network</em>,
    for KAB affiliates, highlights program and project ideas from
    affiliates, educational resources, and national initiatives
    from KAB. </p>
    <p><strong>Special Projects Division&#151;</strong>Affiliates
    can order promotional items such as car litterbags, book
    jackets, and activity books for children. Many items can be
    printed with the affiliate's name or that of a local sponsor. </p>
    <p><strong>Coordinators Advisory Council&#151;</strong>Local
    KAB affiliate coordinators and one state leader serve on the
    council. The council relays feedback from local affiliates to
    KAB staff and committees, and provides an additional source
    of information from KAB to its affiliates. </p>
    <p>To support the involvement of its affiliates in solid
    waste education and solid waste management, KAB and its Solid
    Waste Committee of public and private-sector members develop
    resources for local use. These include:</p>
    <p><a href="study.html"><strong>&quot;The Role of Recycling
    In Integrated Solid Waste Management to the Year 2000&quot;</strong></a><strong>&#151;</strong>KAB's
    national study of recycling and solid waste provides solid
    waste officials with data and forecasts to assist in planning
    the most effective local management possible.</p>
    <p><strong>Waste in the Workplace&#151;</strong>Provides the
    commercial sector with guidelines for auditing waste,
    identifying recyclables, minimizing waste, and reducing
    disposal costs.</p>
    <p><strong>Household Appliance Recovery Kit&#151;</strong>Enables
    coordinators to educate the community about the importance of
    appliance recovery, the steps involved, and related Clean Air
    Act issues.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Teacher Curricula</h3>
<p>Two teacher curricula&#151;<a href="teachers.html#wip"><em>Waste
in Place</em></a> for grades K-6 and <a href="teachers.html#wahr"><em>Waste:
A Hidden Resource</em></a> for grades 7-12&#151;help tomorrow's
decision-makers understand the integrated approach to managing
solid waste and preventing litter. Teacher training institutes
are organized by affiliates and led by a KAB National Education
Consultant. To supplement classroom activities, KAB also offers
resources such as the &quot;200 Million Tons of Trash&quot;
poster, which provides hands-on activities, and fact sheets. An
Education Committee of professional educators from the public and
private sectors guide the development of these teacher resources
and other KAB education initiatives.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Certification and Annual Network Service Fees</h3>
<p>Keep America Beautiful affiliates are required to pay a
one-time Certification Fee. The fee covers the Organizational
Team Training Workshop, where the prospective affiliate's leaders
learn about the KAB System and its implementation; training of
the program coordinator; and the certification process.</p>
<p>An Annual Network Service Fee enables KAB to provide field
counseling and support services for certified affiliates, as well
as KAB's prestigious National Awards Program.</p>
<p><img src="certfees.gif" alt="One-Time Certification Fees"
align="bottom" width="573" height="403"> </p>
<p>For additional information about becoming a KAB Certified
Affiliate, please call (203) 323-8987 and ask for Marjorie
Crosley, or <a href="mailto:keepamerbe@aol.com">e-mail our staff</a>. </p>
<hr>
<p><br>
