Content-length: 7302
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Keep America Beautiful, Inc. - Focus Fact Sheet -
Municipal Solid Waste</title>
<meta name="KEYWORDS"
content="Keep America Beautiful, KAB, MSW, garbage, trash, source reduction, recycling, composting, wte, waste to energy, w-t-e, landfill">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><!--Source code written by Dawn Rosner. FrontPage required for upload, and has tampered with the original coding--></p>
<p><img src="mswbnr.gif" lowsrc="lmswbnr.gif"
alt="Keep America Beautiful, Inc. - Focus Fact Sheet, Municipal Solid Waste"
align="bottom" width="531" height="133"> </p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h3>Facts on Municipal Solid Waste</h3>
<p>In 1994, Americans generated 209 million tons of municipal
solid waste (MSW). Municipal solid waste is defined as waste from
residential, commercial, institutional, and some industrial
sources. It does not include a wide variety of nonhazardous
wastes that usually are landfilled with MSW such as construction
and demolition wastes and automobile bodies. </p>
<p>MSW generation rates are simply estimates, since population
and economics are ever-changing. Nonetheless, natural population
growth and sustained long-term growth in the economy will likely
increase MSW generation; 223 million tons is estimated for the
year 2000. </p>
<p>While tonnage continues to increase, the percentage of MSW
actually disposed of in landfills will decrease due to recycling
and composting efforts. But estimates project a gradually
increasing recycling rate 30% by the year 2000, therefore it is
necessary for communities to consider other waste management
methods that will complement recycling. </p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h3>Composition of Waste Stream</h3>
<p><strong>Materials Generated in MSW by Weight<br>
</strong>(Total Weight = 209.1 million tons)</p>
<p><img src="mswchrt.gif" lowsrc="lmswchrt.gif"
alt="Chart of Composition of Waste Stream" align="bottom"
width="300" height="150"><br>
</p>
<p><em>Source: &quot;Characterization of Municipal Solid Waste
Management: 1995 Update&quot; U.S. Environmental Protection
Agency</em> </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>Managing Municipal Solid Waste</h4>
<p>As the quantity of MSW grows, concern for its safe and
efficient management grows too. Effective waste management
requires what is known as an integrated approach&#151;the
consideration of a number of waste management methods that work
compatibly. These waste management methods include source
reduction, recycling, composting, waste-to-energy, and sanitary
landfill. Together, these methods effectively manage our nation's
waste while, at the same time, protect human health and the
environment. </p>
<p>These waste management alternatives can effectively manage
waste when they are used interdependently, not independently.
Utilizing an integrated waste management approach does not mean
that all of these methods must be implemented, rather it presents
a menu which every community may consider to best fit their
needs. Since each community varies in population, geology,
composition of the waste stream, availability of recycling
markets, etc., waste management methods will also vary.</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h4>Source Reduction</h4>
<p>One way to decrease the amount of waste that needs to be
managed is to not generate it in the first place.
&quot;Preventing waste&quot; is known as source reduction. The
EPA defines source reduction as reducing the quantity of material
that must be discarded, minimizing toxic substances in products,
and manufacturing products with longer, more useful lives.
Manufacturers and consumers alike may take on the responsibility
of preventing waste. For instance, many manufacturers are
eliminating excess packaging from their products. And, many
consumers are reducing waste through such actions as writing on
both sides of a sheet of paper and donating old clothes and
furniture to charity.</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h4>Recycling</h4>
<p>The most commonly collected recyclable materials from homes
and businesses include paper, aluminum, steel, glass, paper, and
plastic. In order for these, and other materials, to be recycled,
we need to complete, or close, the recycling loop. The recycling
loop involves collecting recyclables, separating them, preparing
the recyclable material to buyer's specifications, processing the
material into new products, placing the product back in the
market place, and, consumers purchasing the new product that now
contains recycled material. All of these steps must be completed
before the recycling loop is &quot;closed.&quot; Viable and
stable markets are vital to recycling's success. That is, if
consumers don't buy products made with recycled material,
manufacturers won't have the incentive to buy and process
recyclables into new products. </p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h4>Composting</h4>
<p>The break down of organic materials, such as grass, leaves and
brush, and into a soil-like amendment that may be used for
agricultural and horticultural purposes is known as composting.
This method of managing solid waste is an effective alternative
for states and communities responding to landfill bans on yard
wastes. &quot;Backyard composting&quot; is becoming a household
phrase as more and more homeowners compost organic wastes in
their own backyards.</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h4>Waste-to-Energy</h4>
<p>MSW brought to a waste-to-energy facility is either burned as
received (mass burning) or may be processed to remove
noncombustible materials to produce a more uniform fuel
(refuse-derived fuel). These facilities can reduce the quantity
of MSW by up to 90% while generating steam or electricity.
Emission controls eliminate 99% of air pollutants; and the ash
disposed of in a double lined landfill, does not pose a threat to
groundwater.</p>
<p><br>
</p>
<h4>Sanitary Landfill</h4>
<p>Modern sanitary landfills are state-of-the-art facilities that
manage approximately 61% of our municipal solid waste. Today's
landfills are equipped with monitoring, control, and collection
systems that treat the by-products of waste decomposition. Thus
protecting our air, land, and water . Many landfills have closed
in recent years after reaching capacity. Others closed because
they failed to meet today's stringent environmental regulations,
making open &quot;dumps&quot; a thing of the past. Despite the
number of landfill closings, there is no nationwide problem with
disposal capacity. New landfills are being constructed and
existing landfills are expanding their capacity. Sanitary
landfills will always be needed to dispose of nonrecyclable
items, ash from waste-to-energy plants, and residue from
processing recyclable materials.</p>
<hr>
<p>Return to <a href="index.html">Home Page</a>.</p>
<p><a href="garbage.html"><img src="trashbt2.gif"
lowsrc="ltrshbt2.gif" alt="General Info on Waste Management"
align="middle" border="0" width="117" height="149"></a> <a
href="stuff.html"><img src="catgbtn3.gif" lowsrc="lcatgbt3.gif"
alt="Catalog of Material" align="middle" border="0" width="117"
height="149"></a> <a href="kab.html"><img src="kab-but2.gif"
lowsrc="lkabbut2.gif" alt="About KAB" align="middle" border="0"
width="117" height="149"></a> </p>
</body>
</html>
