Content-length: 51131
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Keep America Beautiful, Inc. - Overview of Solid Waste
Management</title>
<meta name="KEYWORDS"
content="Keep America Beautiful, solid waste, MSW, garbage, trash, recycling, landfill, waste-to-energy, wte, source reduction, composting, compost">
<meta name="KEYWORDS"
content="Keep America Beautiful, solid waste, MSW, garbage, trash, recycling, landfill, waste-to-energy, wte, source reduction, composting, compost">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><!--Source code written by Dawn Rosner. FrontPage required for upload, and has tampered with the original coding--></p>
<p><img src="overbnr.gif" lowsrc="loverbnr.gif"
alt="Keep America Beautiful - Overview of Solid Waste Management"
align="bottom" width="531" height="133"> </p>
<h2>Introduction</h2>
<p>Municipal solid waste (MSW) is a term used to represent all
the garbage created by households, commercial sites (like
restaurants, stores, offices etc.) and institutions (like
schools, museums, public parks etc.). MSW also includes things
like packaging and office paper waste from small to mid-sized
factories which are known as &quot;light industrial sites.&quot;
The ebb and flow of the various elements or materials that make
up the totality of MSW is referred to as the municipal solid
waste stream.</p>
<p>As our population has grown&#151;along with the variety and
amount of commercial products that we use&#151;so has the total
amount of MSW that Americans generate in the course of a year. In
fact, MSW volume has increased upwards of 250 percent since
1960&#151;from 88 million tons to over 209 million tons in 1994. </p>
<p>The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) now projects
continuing increases in annual MSW generation at a rate of 1.2%
annually through the year 2000 and beyond. That translates to a
total of 223 million tons of MSW communities will be dealing with
in 2000 and, if EPA's estimates hold, 262 million tons in 2010. </p>
<p><img src="over1.gif" lowsrc="lover1.gif"
alt="Pie Chart, MSW in 1994" align="bottom" width="250"
height="250"> <img src="over2.gif" lowsrc="lover2.gif"
alt="Graph, MSW 1980 - 2000" align="bottom" width="400"
height="250"></p>
<p>The charts on this page illustrate a continuing evolution in
the variety of ways MSW is managed in communities across the U.S. </p>
<hr>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2>Waste Management Basics </h2>
<p>The first thing to remember about MSW management is that what
may in fact be good for one community&#151;environmentally,
economically and in terms of the community's quality of
life&#151;may actually be different than what is good for
another. This determination depends on a range of independent
variables. That's why, to deal effectively with the millions of
tons of garbage we create, we have to entertain a variety of
different options for dealing with the waste. </p>
<p>No single MSW management option alone can manage all of our
nation's waste. For example, recent U.S. EPA research predicts
that recycling and composting&#151;now 24 percent of all MSW
management activity&#151;can possibly be increased to 30 percent
of MSW management activity by 2000, though this will in fact
still require some significant changes in social behavior and in
other key social and economic factors. However even if we
accomplish this, American communities will still face over 156
million tons of garbage that will have to be managed in other
ways. </p>
<p><img src="msw.gif" lowsrc="lmsw.gif"
alt="Pie Chart of MSW by Weight" align="right" hspace="0"
width="358" height="464"> That is why the EPA, as well as many
states and communities across the nation, now actively pursue
what is called an integrated waste management approach to MSW.
The integrated approach offers communities five different waste
management options to choose from depending on their own specific
needs and the prevailing economic and environmental conditions
they face. The primary options (described in detail in the
sections that follow) include source reduction, recycling,
composting, landfilling and waste-to-energy (combustion). </p>
<p>Most communities use several of these options to manage their
waste stream, and many use all of them to some extent. The
important thing in an integrated waste management approach is
that each element of a community's waste stream is handled in the
most effective, cost-efficient, safe and environmentally
beneficial manner realistically practicable in that community.
This way, increments of progress can be sustained in an overall
MSW management program that lasts for the long term. Each of the
integrated waste management options entails both benefits and
costs, which will make it more appropriate in some situations and
less appropriate in others.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2>Source Reduction</h2>
<p>Although there is no universal definition for source
reduction, the EPA defines it as reducing at the source the
amount of material we produce as a society that eventually gets
discarded as garbage. </p>
<p>There is increasing demand today for products that are more
durable and can last longer than products of past generations.
Demand is also up for products that can be reused both for their
original function or different, alternative functions. And there
is solid demand across the board for products and packaging that
minimize or if at all possible eliminate the use of toxic
substances. As a result, &quot;stand-alone&quot; consumer
products with minimal or no packaging, concentrated or bulk
products, and refillable packages are all no longer frills but
indeed staples of the marketplace.</p>
<p>But source reduction is a two way street. In today's
competitive marketplace, businesses find that products designed
for source reduction can not only attract new consumers, but
often mean better profits in manufacturing and distribution.
Emerging technologies have produced new manufacturing materials
and packaging designs that use less material (so they cost less
to produce) and yet perform the same or even do a better job (so
they actually yield more profits when all is said and done.) </p>
<p><br>
<img src="over4.gif"
alt="Table: Reduction in Weights of Soft Drink Containers, 1972 - 1992"
align="left" hspace="5" width="409" height="258"> For example,
some newly developed packages that use a fraction of the material
required in the past are performing as well at preventing
needless spoilage or breakage of products during distribution and
retailing (which can be a hidden but surprisingly significant
source of MSW).</p>
<p>The progress that can be made through market driven source
reduction can be significant. Take soft drink containers. Over
the past several decades, manufacturers have realized weight
reductions of up to 30 percent or more in aluminum and steel cans
and in glass and plastic bottles. For example, in 1972,
one-hundred 12-fluid-ounce aluminum cans weighed 4.5 pounds.
Through improved technology and design, these same 100 cans
weighed only 3.51 pounds in 1992&#151;a 22% reduction. Steel
beverage cans, which have steel sides and aluminum ends, have
also been downsized and are now 40% lighter than they were in
1970. </p>
<p>Since 1977, the popular two-liter &quot;PET&quot; plastic soft
drink bottles have been reduced from 68 grams each to 51 grams, a
25 percent reduction in material used per bottle. When you
consider that more than seven billion of these two-liter PET
bottles are sold annually, the same volume of product is being
delivered to consumers every year, yet with some 250 million
pounds less packaging, almost all of which used to end up at one
time or another in the MSW stream.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2>Recycling</h2>
<p>According to the EPA, American communities recycled or
composted 24 percent of MSW in 1994 (with composting accounting
for about 3 percent of that total). That means that almost 50
million tons of material was diverted to new generations of use.
The chart below further illustrates the breakdown of MSW, showing
the extent to which different materials are being recycled.</p>
<p><img src="over6.gif"
alt="Table:  Materials Generated and Recycled in 1994"
align="bottom" width="385" height="398"></p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>The Market Forces That Ultimately Drive Recycling</h3>
<p>Recycling involves a complex process through which materials
that can be effectively and efficiently reconverted to raw
material for new products are collected from businesses and
residences, then are sold to manufacturers for processing and
reuse in new generations of products.</p>
<p>The continued long term success of recycling as an MSW
management method depends on the maturation of the
business-to-business marketplace for recycled materials and the
consumer marketplace for recycled-content products. When the
recycling economy is working the way it should be, it is a closed
loop in which consumers, product manufacturers and waste haulers
all have a critical sustaining role to play. All elements are
interconnected&#151;none of the players in the process exists in
a vacuum. </p>
<p><img src="over7.gif" alt="Recycling Loop" align="right"
hspace="0" width="432" height="320">The most critical step is the
determination as to whether it is in fact in anyone's interest to
buy collected recyclables of any given material. If the collected
recyclables do have a value, the money that is paid for them
represents the incentive which makes it worthwhile for
communities to collect them in the first place. </p>
<p>But a manufacturer will only buy the collected recyclable
materials and invest in the infrastructure and resources it takes
to process them if their customers are demanding products that
include recycled raw materials, or if it is less expensive for
them to use recycled material as opposed to virgin raw material.
The cycle revolves in this manner continuously, evolving each day
as consumers, manufacturers and waste haulers react to each
others' actions and reactions.</p>
<p>But the extent to which the loop can be continually fed with
new or additional materials for recycling is not infinite.
Several factors come in to play that determine where exactly the
market for any given material as a recycled commodity
&quot;balances&quot; at any given moment. Some materials will
simply be more in demand as a recycled raw material from time to
time than others. That demand can be very cyclical, even
volatile, and is partly a function of economic and other
variables that have nothing to do with MSW or environmental
factors. Consumer demand is also highly cyclical. </p>
<p>There are other variables that characterize the recycling loop
that are more functional, and thus less cyclical, though no less
important to the mix. For example, in some communities, the cost
of transporting materials to the major manufacturers that would
be interested in buying the material simply might not make
economic or environmental sense. Consider the often encountered
scenario in which a community may have a ton of recycled material
to sell, but the only realistic, potential buyer of the recycled
material is thousands of miles away or perhaps even overseas. Or
another scenario in which products using a certain material in
general could be in such low demand at that moment that a
manufacturer cannot even consider any influx of new raw material,
recycled or virgin. </p>
<p>Intense competitive issues within industries also factor into
the equation. As they fulfill their role in the closed loop of
recycling, individual manufacturers have the ongoing competitive
challenge of determining whether or not a certain recycled
material measures up to virgin raw materials in terms of a
product's quality specifications (which are in part dictated by
the changing tastes of their customers), and their cost
structures (which are also a function of consumer and competitor
behavior.) </p>
<p>Even more technical factors can also contribute to the extent
to which a given manufacturer will use recyclables at any given
time. In some manufacturing processes, for example, even tiny
bits of the wrong material in a batch of recyclables makes the
whole batch useless. This is one reason why it is so important to
the success of recycling that we all carefully separate materials
as directed when the collector indicates separation is necessary. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Collection Options for Recycling</h3>
<p>There are three primary options of recyclables collection from
residential sources. Curbside collection involves a waste hauler
or recycler collecting recyclable materials, separated from other
garbage at the household itself. In this case, residents need
only to faithfully separate recyclables from their non-recyclable
garbage and ensure that the materials make it to the curb when
they are supposed to. According to BioCycle magazine, there are
over 7,000 curbside collection programs in the U.S. today serving
121 million Americans. </p>
<p>The two other most common collection options, drop-off centers
and buy-back centers are similar to each other in terms of how
recyclables are actually collected, but are subtly different in
terms of the incentives involved. Drop-off and buy-back centers
are convenient, centrally located facilities where residents can
deposit different recyclable materials into separate bins. They
are typically located in a public or commercial parking lot, a
transfer station or landfill. The major difference between the
two options is that at buy-back centers, residents and businesses
are actually paid for the recyclables they drop-off, most often
based on the total weight of the individual materials they
provide. Drop off centers are usually unattended (which affects
the quality and marketability of the products they collect) and
rely on consumer goodwill as an incentive.</p>
<p>It is important to remember that none of these collection
options comes free of charge, to someone in the process. Most
often that someone is the taxpayer or the consumer. That is why
it is in everyone's interest that a community's collection
program is both environmentally effective and economically
efficient. This fact also has a lot to do with why different
communities can have vastly different systems for collecting
recyclables.</p>
<p>In the commercial sector, the final responsibility for
delivering recyclables to a processing center or recyclables
buyer falls primarily on the shoulders of the individual company
or commercial site. Because commercial operations have a fairly
consistent waste stream, in many cases they can generate quality
recycled material. Also because they have more control over their
waste stream and they generate large quantities of certain
materials, recycling can actually be an important revenue source
for commercial operations. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Materials Being Recycled Today</h3>
<p>Given current technology, not all materials in the MSW stream
are readily recyclable. Nor do all materials have qualities that
currently make them a valuable commodity in the recycling
marketplace. As mentioned before, some commodities may be in high
demand in one area (for example if a processor or manufacturer
that needs that material is nearby) but can be in little or no
demand elsewhere. </p>
<p>That's why communities will often specify that their residents
and businesses recycle only certain materials&#151;which in fact
are the ones that are currently practical and economical
recycling commodities. That specification can change from time to
time as new recycling markets emerge and new technologies
develop. The materials that follow are those most commonly
collected from homes and businesses for recycling.</p>
<p><img src="over10.gif"
alt="Residential and Commercial Recycling" align="bottom"
width="497" height="370"></p>
<p>The breakdown of recycled materials above is indicative of the
fact that commercial sites are large contributors to the
collection of recycled materials. The most commonly recycled
material, corrugated cartons, are primary carriers of
distribution and storage in the commercial sector.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>PAPER</h4>
<p>Americans recovered for recycling 45% of all paper they used
in 1995&#151;up from 41% in 1994&#151;according to the American
Forest &amp; Paper Association (AF&amp;PA). There are many
different types of recyclable paper, called grades. Each has a
unique value that has a lot to do with what kinds of wood fibers
they will yield for papermakers when broken down. <img
src="over11.gif" alt="Table:  Paper Recovery" align="right"
hspace="0" vspace="5" width="308" height="178"></p>
<p>Generally, paper grades can be grouped into four categories: </p>
<p><em><strong>Corrugated Paper</strong></em> includes old
corrugated boxes, kraft (brown) grocery bags, and shipping sacks.
(Corrugated paper represents 55% of all paper recovered.) </p>
<p><em><strong>Newspapers</strong></em> are manufactured in a
unique papermaking process so old newspapers that have been
separated from other grades of paper and collected from homes and
businesses have a distinct value. On the other hand, newspaper
mixed in with other forms of paper can have much less, or even no
value as a recyclable. </p>
<p><em><strong>High Grade Papers</strong></em> refer to
&quot;white&quot; or bleached office papers used in copying
machine and printing applications and other high quality papers
collected from printing plants. High grade papers represent the
most eagerly sought after form of recycled paper, and can be used
to produce the highest quality recycled paper products.</p>
<p><em><strong>Mixed Papers</strong></em> are groups of different
grades and colors of paper which are used in the manufacture of
various products, such as lower-quality printing and writing
papers, tissue, and recycled paperboard.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>ALUMINUM</h4>
<p>Aluminum has a long history of recycling mainly because
recycled aluminum as a raw material can provide significant
energy savings compared to use of virgin aluminum raw materials
(mainly the ore bauxite).</p>
<p><img src="over12a.gif" alt="Aluminum Can Reclamation"
align="right" hspace="5" width="300" height="212">Today, nearly
100 billion aluminum beverage cans are manufactured each year in
the U.S. alone. Approximately 64 percent of these cans are
recycled. In fact, the recycling infrastructure for aluminum cans
is so efficient now that it can take as few as 90 days for an
aluminum can to be collected, melted down, and made into a new
can ready for distribution. Every aluminum beverage can now on
the market has an average of 54 percent recycled aluminum.</p>
<p>Other aluminum products that can be readily recycled include
foil wrap, food cans, pie plates, frozen food trays, lawn chair
tubing, storm door and window frames, residential siding, and
auto parts. Altogether, aluminum from recycled cans and other
products accounts for about 32 percent of the industry's metals
supply.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>STEEL</h4>
<p>Most steel products can be recycled into new products many
different times. Today, for example, steel-based packaging
products produced in the U.S. have at least 25 percent recycled
steel. (Structural steel, used in erecting bridges, buildings and
the like, is less likely to use large amounts of recycled steel,
given current technology, due to engineering and quality-control
considerations.) </p>
<p><img src="over12s.gif" lowsrc="lover12s.gif"
alt="Steel Can Recycling Rates" align="right" hspace="5"
width="305" height="331"> A variety of consumer products, ranging
from food to paints and cleaning products, are packaged in steel
cans. And according to the Steel Recycling Institute, 55.9
percent of all steel cans were recycled in 1995, representing
significant growth in recycling compared to just 1989 when only
18% of steel cans were being recovered by consumers for
recycling.</p>
<p>While food and beverage cans were originally the major steel
material collected from households, many communities are now
actively recycling other steel-made items such as empty aerosol
and paint cans in their collection programs. (In some
communities, even the remaining paint in the cans is being
collected for recycling.)</p>
<p>In all, more than 170 million Americans have access to
programs that recycle steel through curbside, drop-off, and
buy-back programs. In addition, each year, millions of tons of
steel scrap from appliances, automobiles, and other products are
also recovered and recycled. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>PLASTICS</h4>
<p>In 1994, the recovery rate for all plastics reached nearly 20
percent. According to a study by R.W. Beck, roughly half the U.S.
population has access to some form of plastics collection,
including drop-off collection centers and curbside plastics
collection. That represents a dramatic increase from just a few
years ago. </p>
<p>As far as plastics recycling goes, the most important thing to
remember is that there are many different types of plastics and
each one is unique. Two of the most widely used forms of plastic,
one called &quot;PET&quot; (which stands for polyethylene
terpephthalate) and another referred to as &quot;HDPE&quot; (high
density polyethylene), are now widely recycled, and growth
continues in most other varieties of plastic. </p>
<p>Soft-drink bottles and other rigid containers are among the
most common uses of PET. Approximately 547 million pounds of PET
were recovered for recycling in 1994, up from 447 million pounds
in 1993, making the PET soft-drink bottle the most commonly
recycled plastic container. 48.6 percent of these containers were
recycled in 1994. There are many uses for recycled PET, including
the manufacture of carpet face yarns and fiberfill for products
like sleeping bags and ski jackets. Recently, new recycling and
container fabrication technologies have enabled manufacturers to
use recycled PET in other food packaging applications. </p>
<p>Milk bottles, pigmented (colored) bottles, and soft-drink
&quot;base cups&quot; are all made from HDPE. As with PET, more
HDPE was recovered for recycling in 1994 (537 million pounds)
than in 1993 (444 million pounds). A variety of secondary uses
are being created for recycled HDPE, including new base cups for
PET soft-drink containers, trash cans, detergent and oil bottles,
flower pots, and traffic cones. And, like PET, recycled HDPE is
now appearing in food packaging. Polystyrene (PS) is used in
electronic components, office supplies, housewares, and food
service packaging. In 1994, 34.7 million pounds of polystyrene
were recycled, up from 1.9 million pounds in 1993.</p>
<p>It is important to remember, Polystyrene, HDPE, PET and other
varieties of plastic all have very different properties which
means that they must be separated by consumers and collectors if
they are to become a raw material for new products. One
difficulty that has arisen in the past has been that the
differences between varieties of plastic are not always readily
apparent when comparing the containers visually. </p>
<p>That is why The Society of the Plastics Industry developed a
uniform coding system (shown below) that identifies the type of
resin (the base material from which the plastic is made) which is
used in rigid plastic packaging (like bottles, packages etc.).
This coding system should actually facilitate more and better
quality recycling of plastics when it is economically and
environmentally sensible to do so. The &quot;plastic codes&quot;
now appear on most forms of rigid plastic packaging. Again, it is
critical to the success of plastics recycling that different
plastic items are separated by the household or collector
according to their proper code.</p>
<p><img src="over14.gif" alt="Recycling Symbols" align="bottom"
width="598" height="123"> </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>GLASS</h4>
<p>According to the Glass Packaging Institute (GPI), the glass
container industry recorded a 37 percent recycling rate in 1994.</p>
<p>Recycled glass is made up of cullet, or crushed glass, that is
used in the production of new glass containers. Since 1988, the
amount of cullet used in the manufacture of new containers has
risen substantially. That's because cullet can offer
manufacturers several competitive advantages over virgin
materials. Foremost of these is the fact that cullet melts at
lower temperatures than virgin glassmaking raw materials, and
that allows manufacturers to reduce their energy usage (and
costs) and reduce their air emissions (as well as associated
pollution-prevention costs). </p>
<p>The quality of glass cullet is extremely important to its
recyclability. Glass comes in three colors: flint (which is a
greenish color), clear, and amber (which is brownish). Glass that
is color-sorted and meets specifications is very marketable as a
recycled commodity. Because of the manufacturing processes now
used, cullet that is not color-sorted has little to no value to
container manufacturers. In the years ahead, sophisticated fiber
optics may aid manufacturers in mechanically color-sorting glass,
according to the Glass Packaging Institute. But now the burden
rests primarily on consumers and collectors.</p>
<p><img src="over15.gif" alt="Glass Recycling Rate" align="right"
hspace="0" width="494" height="299"> Contamination is also a
major concern in glass recycling. Processing equipment is
designed to remove contaminants from the glass such as metals,
which are removed magnetically, as well as other items like
aluminum caps and labels that can be removed using other methods.
Still other potential contaminants, such as food residue, remain
with cullet after initial processing but are safely burned off
during the melting process. </p>
<p>However, ceramic materials (such as clay coffee-mugs, plates,
dishes et al.) are the glass industry's number one contamination
problem in the recycling process. What makes these materials
especially troublesome is that, in addition to the fact that they
can ruin a batch of cullet, they are also not easily removed at
any step during processing. That is why it is critical that
ceramics, as well as other types of glass (window glass, baking
glass, and headlight lenses) are removed at or before the point
of collection by consumers or collectors. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>SCRAP TIRES</h4>
<p><img src="over16.gif" alt="Tire Recovery" align="left"
hspace="0" width="287" height="323"> <br>
According to the Scrap Tire Management Council (STMC), 250
million tires become &quot;scrap&quot; or MSW annually&#151;which
is about one tire for every American. </p>
<p>The EPA has reported that two to three billion scrap auto and
truck tires have been either stockpiled or illegally dumped.
There is now a growing market demand for recovered scrap tires.
In 1995, 69 percent of all scrap tires generated were recovered
for recycling and other re-uses, a 26 percent increase from 1994. </p>
<p>Many of the recovered tires are shredded to generate
tire-derived fuel (TDF), which can be used by electric utilities,
pulp and paper mills, and cement kilns. Recent reports have shown
that TDF is comparable to fossil fuel and, in many cases, burns
cleaner and cheaper than coal.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2>Composting</h2>
<p>Composting involves the aerobic, biological decomposition of
organic waste materials (meaning that living microbes combine
with oxygen to cause the decomposition). The end result of
composting is a nutrient-rich, soil-additive called
&quot;compost.&quot; For many years, compostable materials have
contributed millions of tons of material to landfills. Yard
wastes&#151;such as leaves, grass clippings, prunings, and other
natural organic wastes&#151;are in fact the second-largest
component in the MSW stream (comprising 15 percent), behind
paper.</p>
<p>Composting's natural ability to recycle organic materials like
yard waste enables communities to divert a significant portion of
what was once MSW from landfills and into potentially productive
reuses. According to the EPA, composting diverted 3 percent of
MSW from landfills in 1994. Indeed, today, almost half of all
U.S. states now actually ban yard waste from landfills because of
this large volume as well as its potential for being composted.
Markets are now slowly maturing for the finished product&#151;the
compost&#151;which means future incentives could possibly
increase collection and processing of compostable materials down
the road. Compost is already widely used in agriculture and
horticulture (gardening), golf course construction and in
creating landfill cover (the layer of soil that is placed over
old landfills after they have reached capacity.)</p>
<p>Researchers in industry and in government are now studying
composting as a recycling method for some paper wastes that
cannot be effectively recycled into new paper products for one
reason or another. These applications could include composting of
paper products that have been in contact with messy foods at
restaurants or grocery stores, or scraps of papers that are too
small to effectively use as fiber for new papers. Research is
also being conducted into the potential for composting food waste
from commercial sources. Today, there are an estimated
2,000&#151;2,300 municipal yard waste composting sites. There are
also innumerable &quot;backyard&quot; composting programs, whose
popularity is increasing among homeowners. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2>Waste-To-Energy (Combustion)</h2>
<p>Waste-to-energy generation (WTE), the process through which
wastes are collected and combusted to create steam or
electricity, is an effective method of solid waste management and
landfill volume reduction that many communities now rely on.</p>
<p><img src="w-t-e.gif" alt="Waste-to-Energy Plant Diagram"
align="bottom" width="497" height="340"></p>
<p>While the science of the environmental impact of WTE, the
technology of materials extraction and the intricacies of the
economics associated with WTE processes are complex, the
essential process of WTE is not complicated. Quite simply,
instead of being trucked to a landfill, solid waste is brought to
a waste-to-energy plant and is burned at high heats in a process
that creates steam or electricity that is, in turn, sold to
electric generating utilities who distribute it to local homes
and businesses. WTE does not eliminate all the MSW volume of the
solid waste it receives. In fact, about 10 percent of the
original volume is left over after combustion in the WTE furnace
(most often called the boiler) as ash that itself must be either
recycled or landfilled. The recyclable metals that are left over
after incineration are collected and sent to processors for
recycling. </p>
<p>Recycling in fact improves the efficiency of WTE plants by
encouraging the removal of non-combustibles such as glass and
metal, allowing the MSW to burn at a higher heat and thereby
reducing the amount of ash produced. According to the Integrated
Waste Services Association, communities with WTE plants still
recycle an average of 25 percent of their MSW, which is
competitive with non-WTE communities. </p>
<p>Today, 121 WTE facilities manage approximately 16 percent of
all MSW generated nationwide, according to the Integrated Waste
Services Association. Meanwhile, these facilities generate enough
energy each year to power more than one million homes, roughly
the same amount of energy that is supplied by 50 million barrels
of oil. </p>
<p>According to a study conducted by the U.S. Conference of
Mayors and the American Society of Mechanical Engineers, besides
its ability to decrease landfill bulk of a load of MSW by up to
90 percent, a major advantage of WTE is that the energy produced
in the process is generated with about the same environmental
impact as energy produced from natural gas, and with less of an
environmental impact than energy produced from oil or coal.</p>
<p>In fact, the U.S. Department of Energy has identified WTE
technology as a major component of a plan to reduce carbon
dioxide emissions in America over the long term. According to
IWSA, modern WTE plants usually replace older oil or coal burning
facilities, which translates to improved air quality in the
communities where they operate.</p>
<p>Three primary WTE technology options are available:</p>
<blockquote>
    <p><strong>Mass Burn</strong> systems burn MSW as it arrives
    at the plant, without any processing or separation. The fire
    that is created heats boilers, producing steam for industrial
    uses or for generating electricity. These plants represent
    about three-fourths of U.S. WTE plants and each burns between
    200 and 750 tons of MSW each day. Mass burn facilities are
    sized according to the everyday amount of solid waste they
    can expect (larger in a major metropolitan area, smaller in a
    rural area). </p>
    <p>Most mass burn plants can remove non-combustible steel and
    iron for recycling automatically using magnetic separation
    processes. Other non-ferrous metals can be removed from the
    leftover ash as well, also for recycling.</p>
    <p><strong>Modular Incinerators</strong> are small mass burn
    plants, with a capacity of 15 to 100 tons per day. The
    boilers for modular incinerators are built in a factory and
    shipped to the WTE site, rather than being built on the WTE
    site itself. The main advantage of a modular incinerator WTE
    is that it is flexible to a community's growth, and its
    prevailing economic conditions. If more capacity is needed,
    for example, and if the community is in a position to afford
    it, new modular WTE units can be added. These facilities are
    used primarily by small communities and also by industrial
    sites. However, costs limit the use of this technology
    because the return on investment in terms of energy produced
    over time is much lower than in mass burn plants.</p>
    <p><strong>Refuse-Derived Fuel (RDF)</strong> plants process
    solid waste before it is burned. A typical plant will remove
    non-combustible items, separating things like glass, metals
    and other materials for recycling if possible. The
    combustible solid waste remaining is then shredded into
    smaller pieces for burning. RDF plants require significantly
    more sorting and handling than mass burn, but this can
    provide additional opportunities to recover recyclables and
    remove potentially environmentally harmful materials prior to
    combustion. The RDF produced using these methods can be
    burned in power boilers at factories or even at large housing
    complexes. Or they can be used at existing WTE facilities. </p>
    <p>Sometimes RDF materials are densified (or compacted at
    high pressure) into fuel pellets. The &quot;pellet fuel&quot;
    can also include sludges of different kinds that are
    by-products of water treatment in municipal or industrial
    sewage treatment plants. A major advantage of pellet fuel as
    an RDF is that a user can burn it along with other kinds of
    fuel in their existing power boilers. In essence, that means
    RDF pellet fuels can compete with traditional fuels such as
    coal on the open market.</p>
</blockquote>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Air Emissions</h3>
<p>New EPA rules which became effective in 1995 are among the
most stringent environmental standards for WTE facilities in the
world. These rules mandate that all facilities use the most
modern air pollution control equipment available to ensure that
what comes out of WTE smokestacks is as clean as possible, and is
safe for human health and the environment.</p>
<p>The fact is, burning any fuel, including MSW, can produce a
number of pollutants, including carbon monoxide, sulfur dioxide
and fine particles containing heavy metal compounds. Also, other
toxic organic compounds such as dioxins are potential emissions
of any combustive activity where certain chemical compounds are
present, a situation that could take place in the WTE process.
The issue of primary concern, however is whether the
concentrations of these compounds released into the air can be
harmful to human health or the environment. </p>
<p>According to the International Waste Services Association, WTE
processes reduce potential air pollutants to &quot;benign&quot;
levels, and in many cases prevent them entirely, due to extremely
high temperatures that exist in the WTE boilers. In addition,
other air pollution &quot;scrubbing&quot; devices (which are
described below) capture gases that leave the boilers in order to
prevent any potentially harmful emissions that may have somehow
survived the high temperatures. Air emission control devices in a
WTE facility usually include:</p>
<blockquote>
    <p><strong>Dry Scrubbers</strong> which &quot;wash&quot; the
    air emissions of the WTE (called the gas stream) and also
    remove any acidic gases by passing the gas stream through a
    liquid.</p>
    <p><strong>Electrostatic Precipitators (ESP)</strong> use
    high voltage electricity to remove up to 98 percent of all
    particles possibly remaining in the gas stream after passing
    through the scrubbers, including any heavy metal particles.</p>
    <p><strong>Fabric Filters (Baghouses)</strong> consist of a
    series of nearly two thousand fabric bags made of
    heat-resistant material which also filter remaining particles
    from the gas stream. According to the National League of
    Cities, fabric filters capture 99 percent of the particles
    that remain in the gas stream after the scrubber. This
    includes any large concentrations of condensed toxic organic
    compounds (such as dioxins) and heavy metal compounds that
    may remain.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>In a properly operated facility, the air that makes it through
the pollution controls described above and into the smokestack is
&quot;clean&quot; by EPA standards. Smokestack height is an
extra, final precaution taken to assure that remaining pollutants
in the gas stream do not reach the ground in a concentration that
could even be potentially harmful. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Ash Management</h3>
<p>Waste-to-energy produces two types of ash, bottom ash and fly
ash.</p>
<blockquote>
    <p><strong>Bottom Ash</strong> includes both large and
    moderate-sized unburned and unburnable matter that remains
    after the MSW has passed through the furnace, or combustion
    chamber. This ash comprises 75-90 percent of all ash produced
    in a WTE, depending on the technology employed. </p>
    <p><strong>Fly Ash</strong> is a powdery material suspended
    in the gas stream that is collected in the pollution control
    equipment. It tends to have higher concentrations of metals
    and organic materials.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Bottom ash and fly ash are usually combined when collected at
the WTE to facilitate storage, handling, and transportation. A
major benefit of combining the two forms of ash is that it binds
metal particles to other materials and reduces the potential that
these metals will ever leach into ground water once they are
disposed. By law, all of the ash is tested in accordance with EPA
rules before leaving the WTE facility to ensure it is safe for
disposal and possible reuse. </p>
<p>According to IWSA, research now indicates that ash from WTEs
can indeed be used safely and beneficially. One potential for
commercial reuse of WTE ash is in landfills as daily and final
cover material in place of soil. (Currently, as you'll read
later, MSW deposited in landfills is covered by dirt or another
material on a daily basis to prevent windblown litter and for
other reasons.) Ash can also be used as a substitute for the
aggregate used in road base materials, as well as in building
construction and as part of artificial offshore reefs. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
</p>
<h2>Sanitary Landfills</h2>
<p>The sanitary landfill is an engineered method of disposing of
MSW in the minimum amount of space using means that protect human
health and the environment. Communities use landfills to dispose
of millions of tons of the trash they create even if alternative
options like recycling, composting, WTE and source reduction are
operating at maximum efficiency. In 1994, U.S. landfills, all of
them now state-of-the-art facilities, managed about 61 percent of
MSW, according to the EPA. </p>
<p><img src="landfill.gif" alt="Landfill Diagram" align="bottom"
width="472" height="271"> </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>Environmental Considerations</h3>
<p>Properly operated modern landfills are environmentally safe
means of disposal, and are closely monitored for their
environmental impact by the EPA, as well as state and local
authorities. 2,893 MSW landfills now exist in the U.S. according
to a 1995 study by the Environmental Industry Association. </p>
<p>While this is significantly less than the number of landfills
that existed just 25 years ago, it does not indicate that we face
a landfill disposal shortage or crisis of any kind. In reality,
landfill capacity for most states has increased as larger,
modern, privately-owned and operated landfills, known as
megafills, are being built to replace the smaller, &quot;town
dumps&quot; of the past.</p>
<p>By no means are modern landfills anywhere near to being
&quot;simply a hole in the ground where garbage is buried.&quot;
In fact the enforcement of strict environmental standards in the
last decade has played a major role in decreasing the overall
number of landfills. Prior to the mid-1970s, several landfills
around the nation were indeed basically open pits that accepted
all forms of garbage including hazardous wastes. Practices like
these are no longer permitted, and are in fact closely monitored
by government authorities as well as civic and environmental
groups. Municipal solid waste landfills (MSWLs) are now tightly
regulated under Subtitle D of the Resource Conservation and
Recovery Act (RCRA, sometimes spoken as &quot;rickrah&quot;)
passed by Congress in 1976. In 1991 the U.S. EPA published a new
set of strict Landfill Rules that now serve as the basis for
state regulatory and permitting requirements.</p>
<p>Landfills that were in operation on the date of the issuance
of the EPA rules have until October 1997 to either comply fully
with these new environmental regulations or must close in a
responsible manner stipulated by the regulations. That means, the
landfill operators of facilities that can't comply must undertake
an extensive series of mitigation and land reclamation processes.
Most new landfills and any expansion of existing landfills must
fully comply with the EPA rules already. </p>
<p>Because today's landfills need to operate with unquestioned
safety and efficiency, it often can take five or more years from
the time a site is selected until designs, permit applications,
and public hearings are completed and the facility is built. In
addition to complying with EPA rules, many factors are taken into
consideration when siting a landfill. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h3>How a Landfill Operates </h3>
<p>Obviously, in its most basic sense, a landfill is a place
where garbage is hauled, deposited and then buried. But if you
look at a modern landfill in closer detail it is really much more
complicated than that. A typical, modern landfill is divided into
a series of sections called cells. When the solid waste is hauled
to a landfill, it isn't just strewn haphazardly. Rather it is
placed on what is called a working face, which is a portion of a
landfill cell that is currently exposed and available for trash
disposal. Only limited sites in the landfill are exposed at any
given time to minimize exposure of the landfill's contents to
elements like wind and rain. In fact, because a landfill is
filled so systematically, often modern landfill operators can
pinpoint where a specific truck's load of garbage was deposited
even days, weeks or months afterward. </p>
<p>At the conclusion of each day's activity in a cell, a layer of
earth (or as noted before, another material such as ash) called
daily cover is spread across the compacted waste in the cell to
minimize odor, prevent windblown litter, and prevent insect and
vermin problems. The daily cover may also consist of a layer of
foam materials or sheets of synthetic materials. The landfill
operator moves from working face to working face, and from cell
to cell as the landfill gradually fills over periods of many
years, even decades. </p>
<p>But as noted, a modern landfill is more than just a hole in
the ground where we dump trash and forget it. Today's landfills
include multiple safeguards to contain wastes and isolate them
from surrounding water and soil. In many cases, for example, such
safeguards involve a protective liner to prevent filtration.
Liners may be made of compacted clay or impermeable materials
such as plastic. When clay is used, the layer may be as much as
ten feet thick. All this site preparation is done so that any
liquid entering the landfill can be controlled and treated
externally, or retained inside the landfill, rather than being
permitted to pass through the site and come out the other side.</p>
<p>Rain, snow, and other liquids created by the compaction and
decomposition of solid waste that can seep from a landfill cell
is known as leachate. Leachate is considered by EPA and landfill
operators as a potential pollutant of surface waters like lakes,
rivers, streams or the ocean&#151;or groundwater which is the
source of most of our drinking water. With this in mind, a
network of drains is installed at the bottom of the landfill to
collect any leachate that has percolated through the wastes of
the landfill. The leachate is then pumped to waste water recovery
points for treatment. </p>
<p>Groundwater monitoring wells are installed around the
perimeter of the landfill to ensure that surrounding groundwater
is not contaminated with leachate. Should a liner system fail by
breaking or deteriorating, leak detectors installed under the
liners would signal the presence of leachate, allowing immediate
corrective action to take place that prevents any further
movement of leachate from the landfill toward nearby groundwater
or surface waters.</p>
<p>Gases emanating from the landfill are also closely monitored
and controlled. As the organic portion of waste (i.e., food and
yard wastes) decomposes in a landfill, large amounts of methane
gas and carbon dioxide are produced. Methane is controlled. As a
result, under RCRA and the Clean Air Act, landfills are required
to monitor gas both on their surfaces and around their
boundaries. </p>
<p>As cells to the landfill are sealed off, venting systems are
installed that prevent the methane from diffusing underground.
Equipment is also installed in the vents to collect the gas that
emanates from the landfill and burn it off. In many cases, energy
is recovered from the combustion of the gases which is used on
site or sold to local homes or businesses.</p>
<p>All landfills are required to close consistent with certain
&quot;final cap&quot; environmental requirements imposed by EPA.
When landfills as a whole have reached their capacity, they are
covered with a final layer of clay and dirt and then are
re-landscaped according to closure plans drawn up in accordance
with the community. Just to be granted their license to operate
in the first place (even from day one in the case of new
landfills) operators must have a complete plan for when the site
is eventually closed, which in some case can be fifty or more
years down the road. They are also required to provide financial
assurance that ensures that financial means will exist for all
closure, post-closure and corrective action activity over the
lifetime of the landfill. </p>
<p>Once a landfill is capped, the landfill's operators are
obligated to monitor the site for gas and leachate for a minimum
of 30 years after the closure date. They also are often involved
in the ongoing efforts to reclaim the land for other uses.
Landfills can end up in time as open space for communities to use
as parks, ski slopes or even golf courses. Building any permanent
structures on landfills is less common because, as solid waste
decomposes in the landfill, the entire landscape can settle.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<hr>
<p><br>
</p>
