<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3O/DTD HTML//EN">

<html>
<head>
<title>Keep America Beautiful, Inc. - Appliance Recycling</title>
<meta name="KEYWORDS"
content="Keep America Beautiful, recycling, KAB, appliance, steel, illegal dumping">
<meta name="GENERATOR" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
<meta name="FORMATTER" content="Microsoft FrontPage 1.1">
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<p><!--Source code written by Dawn Rosner. FrontPage required for upload, and has tampered with the original coding--></p>
<p><img src="frdgbnr.gif" lowsrc="lfrdgbn.gif"
alt="Keep America Beautiful, Inc. - Appliance Recycling"
align="bottom" width="531" height="133"> </p>
<p><img src="fridge.gif" lowsrc="lfridge.gif" alt="Refrigerator"
align="left" hspace="0" width="163" height="358"> </p>
<h4>Buying A New Appliance</h4>
<p>Every year, Americans discard over 8 million old or broken
appliances. Dryers that don't dry. Washers that don't wash.
Freezers that can't freeze, and ovens that won't heat. <img
src="pigbank.gif" lowsrc="lpigbank.gif" alt="Piggy Bank"
align="right" hspace="0" width="81" height="102"> </p>
<p>We also replace older appliances because we want the
convenience of new features, or to reduce our home's energy
consumption. New appliances can use up to 50% less
energy&#151;which means we pay a smaller electric bill and help
conserve energy. </p>
<p>You may be thinking about buying a new appliance. Perhaps you
already have. If so, there are some important facts you should
know about disposing of your old appliance properly. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>Appliances and the Environment</h4>
<p>Until recently, many worn-out appliances were simply put in
landfills. Today, a growing number of states are prohibiting this
for two reasons. Appliances take up too much space, and they
contain valuable metals that can be easily recovered and re-used. </p>
<p>Whether recycled or landfilled, proper handling of an
appliance is important to protect our environment. You can do
your part by having an old unit removed by the store where you
purchased the new one (and finding out how they dispose of them);
having it removed by a reputable scrap recycler; by donating an
old working unit to charity; or by participating in an appliance
collection day in your community. </p>
<p>Refrigerators and freezers that cool our food contain
chlorofluorocarbon (CFC), a refrigerant that can harm the ozone
layer when released in the air. Under the federal Clean Air Act,
the use of CFC is being phased out. However, if your old
appliance contains CFC, it can be safely removed by a trained
technician. </p>
<p>Appliances made before 1979 may also have motors or other
electric parts with polychlorinated biphenyls (PCBs), an
insulator. Once your appliance has been collected, any PCBs can
be removed and properly disposed. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>Appliance Recycling</h4>
<p><img src="magnet.gif" lowsrc="lmagnet.gif" alt="Magnet"
align="left" hspace="0" width="106" height="169"> Recycling
appliances isn't new! In fact, it's estimated that half of all
major household appliances are currently being recycled to
collect scrap steel, copper, and aluminum. </p>
<p>After any CFCs or PCBs have been removed, your appliance is
shredded. The steel is separated and shipped to a mill, where it
can be remade into one of many new products. The other metals are
also separated and sent to mills. The remaining
material&#151;rubber, plastic, and glass&#151;is called
&quot;fluff,&quot; and can be landfilled.</p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>Illegal Dumping</h4>
<p><img src="nodump.gif" lowsrc="lnodump.gif" alt="No Dumping"
align="right" hspace="0" width="107" height="78"> Making sure
your old appliance is handled properly can also prevent it from
becoming illegally dumped. Such dumping poses many problems. An
abandoned appliance is an invitation for other people to do the
same, spoiling our landscape. Vermin can breed in them, and CFCs
or PCBs may leak into the air or soil. </p>
<p>Illegally dumped appliances also pose dangers to children, who
may become trapped inside while playing. Older refrigerators and
freezers with door latches are especially hazardous, and many
states require that doors on these units be removed to prevent
accidents. </p>
<p><br>
<br>
</p>
<h4>Tips on Disposal and Recycling</h4>
<p><em><strong>Do</strong></em><em> consider donating a working
appliance to charity.</em></p>
<p><em><strong>Do</strong></em><em> ask the store where you buy a
new appliance if it will remove the old unit.</em></p>
<p><em><strong>Do</strong></em><em> learn if your community is
planning an appliance collection day.</em></p>
<p><em><strong>Do</strong></em><em> use a reputable scrap
recycler and ask for a receipt to show that the appliance has
been properly handled.</em></p>
<p><em><strong>Don't</strong></em><em> be an illegal
dumper&#151;others will follow your example. Research by Keep
America Beautiful, Inc. shows that some people will dump and
litter where material has already accumulated.</em> </p>
<p><br>
<br>
<em>This brochure was prepared by Keep America Beautiful, Inc.
and sponsored as a public service by: </em></p>
<blockquote>
    <p><em>The American Iron and Steel Institute<br>
    The Association of Home Appliance Manufacturers<br>
    The Institute of Scrap Recycling Industries<br>
    Steel Recycling Institute<br>
    U.S. Environmental Protection Agency</em></p>
</blockquote>
<hr>
<p>Return to <a href="index.html">Home Page</a>.</p>
<p><a href="garbage.html"><img src="trashbt2.gif"
lowsrc="ltrshbt2.gif" alt="General Info on Waste Management"
align="middle" border="0" width="117" height="149"></a> <a
href="stuff.html"><img src="catgbtn3.gif" lowsrc="lcatgbt3.gif"
alt="Catalog of Material" align="middle" border="0" width="117"
height="149"></a> <a href="kab.html"><img src="kab-but2.gif"
lowsrc="lkabbut2.gif" alt="About KAB" align="middle" border="0"
width="117" height="149"></a> </p>
</body>
